[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research into this topic is fairly new, with few studies published before 2009, but has gained increasing attention in recent years.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A cross-sectoral, holistic approach is seen as an important feature of 100% renewable energy systems and is based on the assumption "that the best solutions can be found only if one focuses on the synergies between the sectors" of the energy system such as electricity, heat, transport or industry.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] No uniform definition for 100% renewable energy systems has been adopted across the published literature.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Recent studies show that a global transition to 100% renewable energy across all sectors – power, heat, transport and desalination well before 2050 is feasible.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Existing technologies, including storage, are capable of generating a secure energy supply at every hour throughout the year.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The sustainable energy system is more efficient and cost effective than the existing system.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) stated in their 2011 report that there is little that limits integrating renewable technologies for satisfying the total global energy demand.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Barriers to implementing the renewable energy plan are seen to be "primarily social and political, not technological or economic".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main obstacle against this scenario is the lack of political will.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] His conclusions have been disputed by other researchers.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson published a response that disputed the piece point by point and claimed that the authors were motivated by allegiance to energy technologies that the 2015 paper excluded.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson says that energy costs today with a wind, solar, and water system should be similar to today's energy costs from other optimally cost-effective strategies and he has rebutted their criticisms.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A followup paper was published by Jacobson and others in 2022, in which paths to 100% renewable energy by 2035 and 2050 were developed for 145 countries.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study concluded that a wind-water-solar (WWS) based system "requires less energy, costs less, and creates more jobs than business as usual".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The cost reduction was primarily due to the substantial (-56.4%) decrease in overall energy demand thanks to the increased efficiency of relying on renewable electricity for all energy needs.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2014, renewable sources such as wind, geothermal, solar, biomass, and burnt waste provided 19% of the total energy consumed worldwide, with roughly half of that coming from traditional use of biomass.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest sector in terms of energy consumption is electricity with a renewable share of 22.8%, most of it coming from hydropower with a share of 16.6%, followed by wind with 3.1%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018, according to REN21, transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy .
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] At the national level, at least 30 nations already have renewable energy contributing more than 20% of the energy supply.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown more quickly than even advocates anticipated.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2019, however, it needs to grow six times faster to limit global warming to 2 °C (3.6 °F).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] 100% renewable energy in a country is typically a more challenging goal than carbon neutrality.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The latter is a climate mitigation target, politically decided by many countries, and may also be achieved by balancing the total carbon footprint of the country (not only emissions from energy and fuel) with carbon dioxide removal and carbon projects abroad.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2018 according to REN21 transformation is picking up speed in the power sector, but urgent action is required in heating, cooling and transport.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] There are many places around the world with grids that are run almost exclusively on renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow of Princeton University have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow us to maintain our quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The main barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low-carbon energy strategies are political rather than technological.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to the 2013 *Post Carbon Pathways* report, which reviewed many international studies, the key roadblocks are: climate change denial, the fossil fuels lobby, political inaction, unsustainable energy consumption, outdated energy infrastructure, and financial constraints.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Studies have shown that Southeast Asia countries could achieve almost 100% renewable elecitricity based on solar, wind, and off-river pumped hydro energy storage at a competitive LCOE of around US$55–115/MWh.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Using 100% renewable energy was first suggested in a paper in *Science* published in 1975 by Danish physicist Bent Sørensen, which was followed by several other proposals.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1976, energy policy analyst Amory Lovins coined the term "soft energy path" to describe an alternative future where energy efficiency and appropriate renewable energy sources steadily replace a centralized energy system based on fossil and nuclear fuels.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 1998, the first detailed analysis of scenarios with high shares of renewables were published.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] These were followed by the first detailed 100% scenarios.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2006, a PhD thesis was published by Czisch in which it was shown that in a 100% renewable scenario energy supply could match demand in every hour of the year in Europe and North Africa.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, Danish Energy professor Henrik Lund published a first paper in which he addresses the optimal combination of renewables, which was followed by several other papers on the transition to 100% renewable energy in Denmark.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Since then, Lund has been publishing several papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] After 2009, publications began to rise steeply, covering 100% scenarios for countries in Europe, America, Australia and other parts of the world.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Even in the early 21st century, it was extraordinary for scientists and decision-makers to consider the concept of 100% renewable electricity.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy use has grown much faster than even advocates had anticipated.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Wind turbines generate 39 percent of Danish electricity, and Denmark has many biogas digesters and waste-to-energy plants as well.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Together, wind and biomass provide 44% of the electricity consumed by the country's six million inhabitants.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2010, Portugal's 10 million people produced more than half their electricity from indigenous renewable energy resources.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Spain's 40 million inhabitants meet one-third of their electrical needs from renewables.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Renewable energy has a history of strong public support.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In America, for example, a 2013 Gallup survey showed that two in three Americans want the U.S. to increase domestic energy production using solar power (76%), wind power (71%), and natural gas (65%).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Far fewer want more petroleum production (46%) and more nuclear power (37%).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Least favored is coal, with about one in three Americans favouring it.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supporters of 100% renewable energy do not consider nuclear power as renewable or sustainable due to perceived risks of disasters and high-level waste management, and consider carbon capture and storage to have limited safe storage potential.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] These constraints have also led to an interest in 100% renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A well established body of academic literature has been written over the past decade, evaluating scenarios for 100% renewable energy for various geographical areas.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In recent years, more detailed analyses have emerged from government and industry sources.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The incentive to use 100% renewable energy is created by global warming and ecological as well as economic concerns, post peak oil.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The first country to propose 100% renewable energy was Iceland, in 1998.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Proposals have been made for Japan in 2003, and for Australia in 2011.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania, Iceland, and Paraguay obtain essentially all of their electricity from renewable sources (Albania and Paraguay 100% from hydroelectricity, Iceland 72% hydro and 28% geothermal).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Norway obtains nearly all of its electricity from renewable sources (97 percent from hydropower).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Iceland proposed using hydrogen for transportation and its fishing fleet.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Australia proposed biofuel for those elements of transportation not easily converted to electricity.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The road map for the United States, commitment by Denmark, and Vision 2050 for Europe set a 2050 timeline for converting to 100% renewable energy, later reduced to 2040 in 2011.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Zero Carbon Britain 2030 proposes eliminating carbon emissions in Britain by 2030 by transitioning to renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2015, Hawaii enacted a law that the Renewable Portfolio Standard shall be 100 percent by 2045.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] This is often confused with renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] If electricity produced on the grid is 65 GWh from fossil fuel and 35 GWh from renewable energy and rooftop off grid solar produces 80 GWh of renewable energy, then the total renewable energy is 115 GWh and the total electricity on the grid is 100 GWh.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Cities like Paris and Strasbourg in France, planned to use 100% renewable energy by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] It is estimated that the world will spend an extra $8 trillion over the next 25 years to prolong the use of non-renewable resources, a cost that would be eliminated by transitioning instead to 100% renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Research that has been published in Energy Policy suggests that converting the entire world to 100% renewable energy by 2050 is both possible and affordable, but requires political support.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] It would require building many more wind turbines and solar power systems but wouldn't utilize bioenergy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other changes involve use of electric cars and the development of enhanced transmission grids and storage.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As part of the Paris Agreement, countries periodically update their climate change targets for the future, by 2018 no G20 country had committed to a 100% renewable target.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Until 2018, there were 181 peer-reviewed papers on 100% renewable energy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In the same year, 100% renewable energy was also mentioned in the Special Report on Global Warming of 1.5 °C as a potential means to "expand the range of 1.5 °C pathways", if the findings can be corroborated.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2021, wind and solar were consistently increasing their share worldwide, but still represented just 5% of global primary energy consumption, albeit far more of useful energy consumption.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Morgan Asset Management (the biggest lender to fossil fuels in the world) analyzed renewable energy forecasts made by eight scientists and research bodies (including Bent Sorensen, Mark Z.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, Amory Lovins) between 1970 and 2020 and claimed that all of them were unrealistically optimistic as they ignored "energy density, intermittency and the complex realities of incumbent energy systems".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some other places have high percentages, for example the electricity sector in Denmark, as of 2014, is 45% wind power, with plans in place to reach 85%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The electricity sector in Canada and the electricity sector in New Zealand have even higher percentages of renewables (mostly hydro), 65% and 75% respectively, and Austria is approaching 70%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] As of 2015, the electricity sector in Germany sometimes meets almost 100% of the electricity demand with PV and wind power, and renewable electricity is over 25%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Albania has 94.8% of installed capacity as hydroelectric, 5.2% diesel generator; but Albania imports 39% of its electricity.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2016, Portugal achieved 100% renewable electricity for four days between 7 and 11 May, partly because efficient energy use had reduced electricity demand.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] France and Sweden have low carbon intensity, since they predominantly use a mixture of nuclear power and hydroelectricity.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018 Scotland met 76% of their demand from renewable sources.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Although electricity is currently around a quarter of world energy supply and consumption; primary energy use is expected to decrease with renewable energy deployment as electricity use increases, as it is likely to be combined with some degree of further electrification.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, electric cars achieve much better fuel efficiency than fossil fuel cars, and another example is renewable heat such as in the case of Denmark, which is proposing to move to greater use of heat pumps for heating buildings to provide multiple kilowatts of heat per kilowatt of electricity.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Other electricity generating sources are considered clean, though not necessarily renewable, as they also do not emit carbon dioxide or other greenhouse gases and air pollutants.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The largest of these is nuclear energy, which produces no emissions.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Some argue that transitioning to 100% renewable energy would be too slow to limit climate change, and that closing down nuclear power stations is a mistake.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Carbon capture and storage projects may still use coal or natural gas but capture carbon dioxide for storage or alternative uses.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Pathways to eliminate greenhouse gases may include these in addition to renewable energy to save money, or to avoid shutting down existing plants and allow for flexibility in designing a carbon-free electric grid.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In 2018, California passed SB 100, which mandates 100% clean, carbon-free by 2045, including a 60% renewable electricity goal by 2030.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] 2019 legislation in Washington also requires 100% clean electricity by 2045, eliminating coal by 2025.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Further states and territories to require 100% carbon-free electricity are Hawaii, Maine, Minnesota, Nevada, New Mexico, New York, Virginia, Puerto Rico, and Washington, DC.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to a study by Global Energy Monitor, China is expected to generate 1,200 gigawatts of renewable energy (wind and solar) by 2025.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Jacobson, the most significant barriers to the widespread implementation of large-scale renewable energy and low carbon energy strategies, at the pace required to prevent runaway climate change, are primarily political and not technological.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] IPCC scenarios "generally indicate that growth in renewable energy will be widespread around the world".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The IPCC said that if governments were supportive, and the full complement of renewable energy technologies were deployed, renewable energy supply could account for almost 80% of the world's energy use within forty years.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Rajendra Pachauri, chairman of the IPCC, said the necessary investment in renewables would cost only about 1% of global GDP annually.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] This approach could contain greenhouse gas levels to less than 450 parts per million, the safe level beyond which climate change becomes catastrophic and irreversible.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Socolow have developed a series of "climate stabilization wedges" that can allow societies to maintain their quality of life while avoiding catastrophic climate change, and "renewable energy sources", in aggregate, constitute the largest number of their "wedges".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown founder and president of the Earth Policy Institute, a nonprofit research organization based in Washington, D.C., says a rapid transition to 100% renewable energy is both possible and necessary.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Brown compares with the U.S. entry into World War II and the subsequent rapid mobilization and transformation of the US industry and economy.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A quick transition to 100% renewable energy and saving of our civilization is proposed by Brown to follow an approach with similar urgency.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to World Bank the "below 2°C" climate scenario requires 3 billions of tonnes of metals and minerals by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Supply of mined resources such as zinc, molybdenum, silver, nickel, copper must increase by up to 500%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A 2018 study analysed the metal requirements to transition the global energy system up to 2060.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Currently used battery technologies and known reserves are not compatible with the transition scenario as a result of insufficient cobalt and lithium reserves.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Batteries containing less or no cobalt are feasible.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Lithium is much more difficult to replace with maintained performance and cost.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review suggests large institutions are prone to resisting "the challenge of 100% RE scenarios based on the dogma that the world cannot do without fossil fuels and nuclear energy".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Institutions that have received extensive criticism include the International Energy Agency and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, with the latter also being criticized for not including studies on 100% RE systems in their IPCC reports.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A report found that China is about to produce "almost 95% of the world's polysilicon and the ingots and wafers" of the solar panel supply chain, with this level of concentration in any global supply chain "would represent a considerable vulnerability".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] One of the main obstacles to 100% renewable energy is the intermittency or variability of renewable energy sources – such as times when sufficient amounts of energy can be generated neither via wind nor via solar power ("Dunkelflauten").
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] According to Amory Lovins the electricity grid alone can compensate for variability, just as it routinely backs up nonworking coal-fired and nuclear plants with working ones.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] For example, it may cost 40% more to reduce carbon emissions without carbon dioxide capture.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The study introduced the term "firm low-carbon energy source" (e.g. nuclear, geothermal), which is intended to operate along "fast-burst" sources (e.g. batteries) and "fuel saving" (VRE).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] The International Energy Agency says that there has been too much attention on issue of the variability of renewable electricity production.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Variability is rarely a barrier to increased renewable energy deployment when dispatchable generation such as hydroelectricity or solar thermal storage is also available.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] But at high levels of market penetration it requires careful analysis and management, and additional costs may be required for back-up or system modification.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Hydropower is currently the only large scale low-carbon seasonal energy storage.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In countries with high variation in energy demand by season (for example the UK uses far more gas for heating in the winter than it uses electricity) but lacking hydropower electrical interconnectors to countries with lots of hydropower (e.g.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] UK - Norway), electricity from hydropower is likely to be insufficient and development of a hydrogen economy would likely be needed: this is being trialled in the UK and 8 TWh of inter-seasonal hydrogen energy storage has been proposed.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] In Australia, as well as storing renewable energy as hydrogen, it is also proposed to be exported in the form of ammonia.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] McKinsey estimates that it will cost 7.5% of global domestic product between 2021 and 2050 to achieve net zero (not 100% renewable, which will be more expensive).
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Current spending is just over half of this.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] A review identified major gaps and neglected aspects – open research questions – in the 100% RE literature.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] Full decaronization of the energy system by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p01] 7.16 for renewable target and 12 for national target.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has said that there are few fundamental technological limits to integrating a portfolio of renewable energy technologies to meet most of total global energy demand.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a 2011 review of 164 recent scenarios of future renewable energy growth, the report noted that the majority expected renewable sources to supply more than 17% of total energy by 2030, and 27% by 2050; the highest forecast projected 43% supplied by renewables by 2030 and 77% by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2011, the refereed journal *Energy Policy* published two articles by Mark Z.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson, a professor of engineering at Stanford University, and research scientist Mark A.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Delucchi, about changing the energy supply mix and "Providing all global energy with wind, water, and solar power".
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The articles analyze the feasibility of providing worldwide energy for electric power, transportation, and heating/cooling from wind, water, and sunlight (WWS), which are safe clean options.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part I, Jacobson and Delucchi discuss WWS energy system characteristics, aspects of energy demand, WWS resource availability, WWS devices needed, and material requirements.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] They estimate that 3,800,000 5 MW wind turbines, 5350 100 MW geothermal power plants, and 270 new 1300 MW hydroelectric power plants would be required.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In terms of solar power, an additional 49,000 300 MW concentrating solar plants, 40,000 300 MW solar photovoltaic power plants, and 1.7 billion 3 kW rooftop photovoltaic systems would also be needed.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Such an extensive WWS infrastructure could decrease world power demand by 30%.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In Part II, Jacobson and Delucchi address variability of supply, system economics, and energy policy initiatives associated with a WWS system.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The authors advocate producing all new energy with WWS by 2030 and replacing existing energy supply arrangements by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Energy costs with a WWS system should be similar to today's energy costs.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In general, Jacobson has said wind, water and solar technologies can provide 100 percent of the world's energy, eliminating all fossil fuels.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] 0.1% of the time would require generation from other sources.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In March 2012, Denmark's parliament agreed on a comprehensive new set of promotional programs for energy efficiency and renewable energy aimed at reaching 100 percent of electricity, heat and fuels from renewables by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] IRENEC is an annual conference on 100% renewable energy started in 2011 by Eurosolar Turkey.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] More recently, Jacobson and his colleagues have developed detailed proposals for switching to 100% renewable energy produced by wind, water and sunlight, for New York, California and Washington states, by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] As of 2014, a more expansive new plan for the 50 states has been drawn up, which includes an online interactive map showing the renewable resource potential of each of the 50 states.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The 50-state plan is part of The Solutions Project, an independent outreach effort led by Jacobson, actor Mark Ruffalo, and film director Josh Fox.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Debate over detailed plans remain, but transformations in global energy services based entirely around renewable energy are in principle technically practicable, economically feasible, socially viable, and so realisable.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] This prospect underpins the ambitious commitment by Germany, one of the world's most successful industrial economies, to undertake a major energy transition, Energiewende.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015 a study was published in *Energy and Environmental Science* that describes a pathway to 100% renewable energy in the United States by 2050 without using biomass.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Implementation of this roadmap is regarded as both environmentally and economically feasible and reasonable, as by 2050 it would save about $600 billion of health costs a year due to reduced air pollution and $3.3 trillion global warming costs.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] This would translate in yearly cost savings per head of around $8300 compared to a business as usual pathway.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to that study, barriers that could hamper implementation are neither technical nor economic but social and political, as most people didn't know that benefits from such a transformation far exceeded the costs.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In June 2017, twenty-one researchers published an article in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* rejecting Jacobson's earlier *PNAS* article, accusing him of modeling errors and of using invalid modeling tools.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] They further asserted he made implausible assumptions through his reliance upon increasing national energy storage from 43 minutes to 7 weeks, increasing hydrogen production by 100,000%, and increasing hydropower by the equivalent of 600 Hoover Dams.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Victor called Jacobson's work "dangerous" and Ken Caldeira emphasized that increasing hydropower output by 1,300 gigawatts, a 25% increase, is the equivalent flow of 100 Mississippi Rivers.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Jacobson published a response in the same issue of the *PNAS* and also authored a blog post where he asserted the researchers were advocates of the fossil fuel industry.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Another study published in 2017 confirmed the earlier results for a 100% renewable power system for North America, without changes in hydropower assumptions, but with more realistic emphasis on a balanced storage portfolio, in particular seasonal storage, and for competitive economics.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2015, Jacobson and Delucchi, together with Mary Cameron and Bethany Frew, examined with computer simulation (Loadmatch), in more detail how a wind-water-solar (WWS) system can track the energy demand from minute to minute.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] This turned out to be possible in the United States for 6 years, including WWS variability by extreme weather events.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2017, the plan was further developed for 139 countries by a team of 27 researchers and in 2018, Jacobson and Delucchi with Mary Cameron and Brian Mathiesen published the Loadmatch results for 20 regions in which the 139 countries in the world are divided.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] According to this research, a WWS system can follow the demand in all regions.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The program has been carried out for each region 10-20 times with adapted input for the storage capacities, until a solution was found in which the energy demand was followed, per half minute for 5 years, with low costs.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In 2020, Jacobson clarified in a textbook computer simulation results of a WWS energy system.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] To match demand with supply every minute more solar and wind farms and high-voltage lines must be installed than to match year-averaged demand and supply.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] Oversizing (also in a conventional energy system) ensures that the demand can be followed during peak hours, but causes unused supply during off-peak hours.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] In a WWS system, more energy exchange between areas leads to more transmission loss.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The table shows WWS supply, unused supply, losses and end-use, in GW average power to reliably supply the world and four major regions with energy by 2050.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] See textbook Table 8.10; energy in TWh is divided by 26.3 kh (1000 hours) to get power in GW.
[src:google/100-renewable-energy-p02] The bottom row is the storage capacity of pumped hydro plants (Table 8.7).
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port of New York Authority began acquiring the land on the building's site in 1930, against the protests of local residents.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] It was completed in 1932 and served as an inland terminal for the Hudson River piers and as a warehousing and industrial facility.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy fell to 50 percent in the 1970s due to the decline of industrial activity in Manhattan, and the Port Authority itself moved to the World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In the 1990s the building began to attract tenants in the technology and telecommunications sectors.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, the building was purchased for $1.8 billion by Google, who became its largest tenant; Google's presence helped attract other technology companies to Chelsea and contributed to the neighborhood's ongoing gentrification.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Aside from Google, the building is also home to a cancer treatment center and a black box theater.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue occupies the full city block between Eighth and Ninth Avenues and 15th and 16th Streets in the Chelsea neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building, completed in 1932, was designed by Lusby Simpson of Abbott, Merkt & Co.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building is 15 stories tall and has 2.9 million square feet (270,000 m2) of floor space, more than the Empire State Building; the individual floors are nearly 4 acres (1.6 ha) in area and have 14.5-foot (4.4 m) ceilings.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] It has a rooftop helipad and penthouse floors on either end of the building.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Its exterior is in the Art Deco style and features recurring seagull motifs.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The walls are largely made of brick, with granite bases; the first two stories are limestone, and copings and finials are of terracotta.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Because of the warehouse mission of the building, it was able to avoid some of the setback rules that greatly reduced the buildable space available for the skyscrapers that mark the Manhattan skyline.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a multipurpose design when it opened in 1932, with the first floor and basement designated as "Union Inland Terminal #1", which was to be used to transport goods by truck to and from railroad lines and shipping piers on the Hudson River.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Cargo was dropped off along 15th Street, sorted inside the building, and picked up from the 16th Street side.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building included four truck elevators, each of which had a 40,000-pound (18,000 kg; 20-short-ton) capacity and could travel at up to 200 ft/min (61 m/min).
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] These elevators measured 17 by 34 feet (5.2 by 10.4 m) across, and they lifted trucks into pits measuring 3.5 feet (1.1 m) deep and 38 by 90 feet (12 by 27 m) across.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] There were also 12 package elevators and 18 passenger elevators.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Freight companies used the elevators to deliver cargo directly to tenants, in contrast to other industrial buildings in New York City, where cargo was dropped off at ground level.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The second floor contained Commerce Hall, designed for exhibitions.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The upper floors were intended for manufacturing.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] There were 16 loading docks on each floor.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] On the 15th floor, which contained the Port Authority's offices, engineer Aymar Embury II designed a 325-seat auditorium decorated in green and blue.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The *New York Herald Tribune* said was the "first auditorium designed for commercial purposes in a strictly commercial structure".
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building's design retains vestiges of its original industrial purpose, including truck-sized freight elevators and floors built to support heavy loads.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] As of 2008, two of its original truck elevators were still in use, in addition to nine other large freight elevators and fourteen passenger elevators.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The floors of the two lobbies originally each had a large bronze seal of the Port Authority embedded in them; one of these was removed and converted into a coffee table as a retirement gift for Port Authority director Austin J.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] It is also noted for its unobstructed views of the Manhattan skyline.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building has direct access to the 14th Street/Eighth Avenue station of the New York City Subway; when the building opened, a staircase at 15th Street and Eighth Avenue led directly to the subway station in the basement.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] By the early twentieth century, the West Side of Manhattan was plagued with heavy traffic because of the tangle of street-level passenger and freight trains on the West Side Line, cargo unloading from the busy Hudson River piers, and the lack of suitable warehouse facilities.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The situation led the Port of New York Authority to commission the construction of a large inland terminal at 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] It was designed to alleviate the traffic problem by streamlining the distribution of goods within a single location.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Instead of cargo being picked up directly at the piers, it would be brought to the building to be consolidated, where trucks could pick up all their cargo in a single stop.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] A concurrent project, the West Side Improvement Project, replaced the West Side Line with the original High Line elevated railway, which ran a few blocks away from 111 Eighth Avenue; it began full operation in 1934.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In May 1930, the Port Authority and all of the railroads in the Port of New York agreed to build a "union inland freight terminal" between Eighth Avenue, 15th Street, Ninth Avenue, and 16th Street.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was planned to cost $15 million and would include office space, as well as large driveways and about 7 acres (28,000 m2; 300,000 ft2) for sorting freight.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The structure was to be known as Inland Terminal No.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] 1 because the Port Authority hoped that similar freight terminals would be constructed across the city.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of the announcement, the Port Authority already owned half of the block, which it had acquired for $1.5 million.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Most of the block had been occupied by houses, except for a factory in the middle of the block on 15th Street.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The New York City Board of Estimate approved the proposed terminal's site in June 1930.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority acquired additional land on the building's site throughout the rest of the year, despite the protests of local residents.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] By October 1930, the Port Authority had bought 85 percent of the site and was preparing to acquire the remaining buildings through condemnation.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] A contract for the demolition of existing structures was awarded in December 1930.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Twelve railroads signed an agreement with the Port Authority to use the new terminal at the beginning of January 1931, and contractors immediately began razing the site.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Godwin Construction Company was contracted in April 1931 to excavate the site and construct the building's foundations.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] A groundbreaking ceremony for the freight terminal, attended by New York State governor Franklin D.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Roosevelt, took place on April 30, 1931.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] That September, the Port Authority received bids for the construction of the building's superstructure; the Turner Construction Company submitted a low bid of $7.591 million.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Construction required 120,000 cubic yards of concrete, 65 miles of piping, and 12 million bricks, as well as 160,000 barrels of cement.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority also paid to widen the streets on all four sides.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Four hundred railroad managers were invited to inspect the new terminal on September 9, 1932.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] 1 was formally dedicated the next week, September 16, though the building was not at that time fully completed.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] At the time it was the largest building in New York City.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building ultimately cost $16 million; the superstructure alone cost $8 million to $9 million.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Shippers and consignees began using a 265,000-square-foot (24,600 m2) freight terminal on the basement and first floor on October 3, 1932.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Only the basement and ground story were open at the time; the upper stories, intended for light manufacturing, were not expected to be completed until the end of the year.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Real-estate experts cited Inland Terminal No.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] 1 as one of several developments that were contributing to the growth of businesses in Chelsea.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The final dedication of the building occurred on February 25, 1933, with a ceremony attended by Port Authority, New York City, and New York state officials.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] A banquet was held in one of the building's truck elevators to mark its dedication.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Tenants had begun moving into the upper stories even before the building's dedication.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] By the beginning of 1933, eight hundred shipping firms were using the terminal to ship outbound freight, while fifty shippers received inbound freight there.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Each railroad paid the Port Authority ten cents for every 1 short ton (0.89 long tons; 0.91 t) of freight handled at the terminal.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal was to be used by all shippers in Manhattan between Houston Street to the south and 23rd Street to the north.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] At the time of construction it was estimated to be capable of handling one-third of the 680,000 annual tons of less-than-carload freight at the port.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Among the terminal's tenants during the 1930s were the Woolworth Company, Rand McNally, the New York Trust Company, and offices of the Works Progress Administration.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority hired Caldwell, Garvan & Bettini in October 1933 to construct a lobby, stair, and foyer for Commerce Hall on the building's second floor.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall opened on December 8, 1933, with an exhibit of Ford Motor Company vehicles.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The terminal saw early success in reducing truck traffic to and from the railheads.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] For instance, on May 25, 1936, 250 trucks brought cargo to the building that was consolidated into only 37 trucks to take to the ferry terminals.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Commerce Hall hosted the National Business Show for several years in the 1930s.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] By February 1938, all of the building's space had been rented, despite the ongoing Great Depression.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] After Commerce Hall was closed in 1938, the floor was converted to regular commercial use.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Board of Estimate approved an agreement in 1940, in which the Port Authority would make annual $60,000 payments in lieu of taxes on the building.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained 95 percent occupied at the time.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Its tenants during the early 1940s included Sears, Roebuck and Company, as well as a regional office for the Second Corps Area.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In spite of a decline in freight traffic during World War II, the Port Authority retained a good credit rating and, by 1945, had drawn up plans for two new freight terminals in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority's 1949 report noted a significant decrease in freight handling at the building due to an overall shift in Manhattan from rail to trucks for transporting goods.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Around this time, the Port Authority constructed additional inland terminals intended for truck traffic: the New York Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1949 and the Newark Union Motor Truck Terminal in 1950.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority began erecting a helipad on the building's roof in November 1950, and the helipad opened on May 31, 1951.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] It was the site of an accident on July 13, 1955, when a Bell 47 helicopter operated by the Port Authority crashed shortly after take-off and fell, in flames, onto the fifteenth floor, where it became stuck.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The pilot and his only passenger survived with injuries.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The last of the railroad companies left the building in 1963.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The shipping and manufacturing industries in Chelsea declined significantly during the 1960s, as firms moved from the neighborhood to elsewhere in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building remained the Port Authority's headquarters until the agency moved to the new World Trade Center in 1973.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Port Authority sold 111 Eighth Avenue to Realopco Inc. – a company operated by brothers Sylvan Lawrence and Seymour Cohn, who also led the Sylvan Lawrence Company – for $24 million in July 1973.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The owners added a CCTV system, replaced existing manually operated elevators with 12 automatic elevators, and refurbished the lobby, and they received a $25 million mortgage from Chase Manhattan Bank.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building had a 40 percent vacancy rate in 1975, a figure that increased the next year to 50 percent.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] This was attributed to the decline of manufacturing in New York City and the ongoing national recession; in addition, several tenants had vacated large blocks of space, including Interstate Stores and Atlantic Department Stores.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Mayor Abraham Beame proposed that the vacant space be leased to garment manufacturers, but many garment firms were loath to relocate.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] After the Sorg Printing Company leased some of the vacant space, the occupancy rate increased to 75 percent by January 1977.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Occupancy had rebounded to 90 percent by 1979.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Following Lawrence's death in 1981, Seymour Cohn and Lawrence's widow Alice each acquired a 50 percent stake in 111 Eighth Avenue.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence were unable to agree on what to do with 111 Eighth Avenue and three other buildings, leading to a protracted legal struggle.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] During the 1980s and 1990s, the building attracted a number of a tenants in the computer industry, who were drawn by the large floor space.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In addition, numerous companies had moved their back office operations to 111 Eighth Avenue by the early 1980s.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building was 80 percent occupied in 1992, with space renting at $8 to $18 per square foot ($86 to $194/m2).
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] By the late 1990s, the building was 87 percent occupied, and Sylvan Lawrence had leased out 200,000 square feet (19,000 m2) during the preceding year.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building's largest tenants at the time included Citibank, the New York State Insurance Fund, and Prudential Securities.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The massive building served as a dwindling warehouse and back-office outpost through the end of the 1990s.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Cohn and Alice Lawrence agreed to sell off 111 Eighth Avenue and Lawrence's other three buildings in 1997.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Blackacre Capital Group and Taconic Investment Partners agreed to acquire the four buildings in November 1997 for $387 million; the sale was finalized in January 1998.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic marketed 111 Eighth Avenue as a carrier hotel for the new booming internet business, as the building had high ceilings, large floor plates, multiple fiber-optic connections, and five times the electrical capacity that typical tenants required.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] This was coupled with the fashionable rise of the Chelsea neighborhood that surrounded it.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic began a $50 million renovation, replacing the building's wiring.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] One-third of the space was leased to telecommunications companies and another one-third to advertising agencies and internet companies.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The new occupants could afford higher rents than the old industrial tenants.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Although Taconic tried to screen potential telecommunications tenants by establishing strict net-worth requirements, so many companies expressed interest in the building that Taconic had stopped accepting new telecommunications tenants by late 1999.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Average rents had more than doubled during the preceding two years, from $18 to $46 per square foot ($190 to $500/m2).
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] A 70,000-square-foot (6,500 m2) cancer treatment center, designed by Gwathmey Siegel & Associates Architects and operated by St.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Vincent's Hospital, opened in the building the same year.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Eighth and Ninth Avenue lobbies were renovated in 2000 and 2004, respectively.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] During the Northeast blackout of 2003, the building was able to keep power on, thanks to an underground fuel tank and 37 generators.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In 2006, the Atlantic Theater Company opened a 99-seat black box theater in the building, and Lifetime Entertainment Services became its first cable television tenant.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Google opened its largest engineering office outside of California in the building in 2006, leasing 300,000 square feet (28,000 m2) across three floors.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Google workspace was noted for its campus-like and playful atmosphere, with perks including free food and a game room; *The New York Times* described it as "a vision of a workplace utopia as conceived by rich, young, single engineers in Silicon Valley, transplanted to Manhattan".
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In 2010, Google contracted to purchase the entire building from Taconic, in a deal reported to be worth around $1.8 billion, the biggest purchase of a U.S. office building of the year.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The deal was credited with helping revive the New York City commercial real estate market, which had slumped during the Great Recession.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] After the purchase, Google was the largest tenant, with 500,000 square feet (46,000 m2) of the building.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Taconic continued to manage the building under contract from Google.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Since its acquisition, the building has become popularly known as the "Google Building", and it is regarded as the company's East Coast headquarters.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] 111 Eighth Avenue is adjacent to trunk fiber optic lines stretching from Hudson Street and continuing up Ninth Avenue.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] That line at the time was owned by Lexent Metro Connect.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] There was speculation at the time of the acquisition that Google would use its strategic location to launch a Google Fiber operation in New York City.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Google Fiber plan never came to pass, and Google has denied it has any plans to bring it to New York City anytime in the near future, although in 2013 it did begin offering free Wi-Fi to its Chelsea neighbors.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The Lexent dark fiber line has been acquired by Lightower Fiber Networks.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] The building's meet-me room in its carrier hotel was one of the main network interconnections in the city as of 2006.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] In 2013 the first class of the newly created Cornell NYC Tech school began classes in the building, in space donated by Google.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Classes continued in the building until the school moved to its new location on Roosevelt Island in 2017.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Despite the massive size of the acquisition, Google has still found itself having to rent space elsewhere because it has been unable to break the leases with some of its tenants, including Nike, Deutsch Inc., and Bank of New York.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] After years of renting additional space across the street in the Chelsea Market, Google purchased that building in 2018.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] Google's expansion in Chelsea helped attract other technology companies to the area and contributed to gentrification.
[src:google/111-eighth-avenue] *The New York Times* described Google as drawing "relatively few complaints" in the neighborhood, and New York City Council speaker Corey Johnson called the company "a good neighbor", although some residents blamed it for changing the neighborhood's character and driving out smaller businesses.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The **2011 Slovenian YouTube incident** was the publication of three clips of the recordings of closed sessions of the Government of Slovenia on the video-sharing website YouTube on 3 December 2011.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The clips were published under the title *Stari obrazi* (*Old Faces*) by someone who signed himself as *stariobrazi* (*oldfaces*).
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The publication happened during the term of the Prime Minister Borut Pahor, just before the early 2011 Slovenian parliamentary election on 4 December.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The first of the clips published was dated to 31 January 2008, when Janez Janša was the Prime Minister.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The second and the third clip was dated to 23 April 2009, respectively 23 April and 30 April 2009, when Borut Pahor was the Prime Minister.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The original recordings were produced in audio and video.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were stored on DVDs and locked in a safe available only to authorised personnel.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were also available at home to three people via the Spectiva remote viewing software, but due to their low quality, the probability of Spectiva being the source of the leaked data has been estimated as low, and it was not used during the term of Pahor's government.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Spectiva could be misused until July 2009.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] It seems most probable that the recordings originated from the recording room or were transferred with additional equipment from the press room of the government; till 2009, sessions were broadcast live there so that extracts of resolutions could be made by the authorised personnel.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Marjan Miklavčič, an expert in intelligence services and a lecturer at the University of Maribor, compared the publication to WikiLeaks.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] He particularly stressed that it was not known which data had been stolen and whether they could be used for extortion.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Iztok Prezelj, who lectures on intelligence at the University of Ljubljana, stated that the publication showed a parallel state to exist in Slovenia.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Miklavčič confirmed that all the data publicly available indicate the thesis about a parallel state to be correct.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The ministers of Janša's government, Andrej Vizjak and Mojca Kucler Dolinar, were discussing the wages of judges.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 9 December, it was reported that the Slovenian Police had started investigation about the clips.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 14 December, the Government spokesperson Darijan Košir explained that in 2006, government areas were renovated.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] He said that the recorded sessions were held at Gregorčič Street 20 (*Gregorčičeva ulica 20*; Government and Presidential Palace) and the recording room was at Gregorčič Street 25.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The buildings were connected with 200 metres (660 feet) of cable.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The system could be abused at several points.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The works at Gregorčič Street 25 were carried out by the construction company SCT, and the computer infrastructure was set up by the companies ADM and TSE.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Košir told that all the people with access to the data were thoroughly checked.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 12 December, after the Secretariat filed a criminal complaint, the Police requested an internal report from the Secretary-General Kamnar.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 15 December, TSE denied having spotted any anomalies in the computer system since it had been installed.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They told that all their employees were checked and that they never received any instruction that would allow for an illegal access.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They also pointed out that the Government was responsible for the security of the system after it had been taken over.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The telephone number of ADM was unavailable.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Rumors about a slow investigation due to long preparation of report by the Secretary-General appeared.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Both the minister of interior and the Secretary-General denied this.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 11 January 2012, an inspectional surveillance, ordered by the Information Commissioner Nataša Pirc Musar, was carried out by the Inspectorate for Protection of Personal Data at the Secretary–General.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] As of 27 January 2012, the findings were not available yet.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The results will influence the decision of the Government about the destruction of the original session recordings.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 26 January 2012, the Secretariat-General of the Government issued a report about an internal investigation that failed to find the perpetrator.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] However, it was found out that the clips were carefully chosen and taken out of context, giving them a different meaning than they would have in the whole.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were alienated after they had been processed in the recording room.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] This significantly narrowed the number of supply locations and the circle of possible suspects.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The highest risk was associated with the human factor.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The Secretariat–General identified the crimes of betrayal of secrets, misuse of position, unauthorized image recording, and an information system attack.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Due to lack of jurisdiction of the Government, further investigation would be carried out by the police.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 27 January 2012, Helena Kamnar, the Secretary-General of the Government, unofficially told for media that three people had access to the Spectiva remote viewing software, and could also watch the sessions from their home.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Kamnar also explained that it was possible to find out who had access in which period but had no information due to the police having confiscated one of the computers.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 28 January 2012, she told that according to the information she had received from the person who allocated the right to use the system, the three people were Janez Janša, the former Secretary-General Božo Predalič, and the former Secretary-General Milan M.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They only had the possibility to use it in their respective terms.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Predalič told that he used it perhaps twice, because he was present at Janša's sessions and did not have the option to use it during Pahor's sessions.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Cvikl told that he refused to use it as it seemed redundant to him and due to security reasons even demanded it to be uninstalled.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The confiscated computers were returned to the Secretary-General on 31 January 2012.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The next morning, Kamnar found the doors of the secretary open and reasoned that someone had broken in.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The Government officially denied any evidence that a criminal act had happened.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] There were guesses whether the two events could be related, but Kamnar decided there would be no investigation, as the possibility of it being successful was slim and she was to be replaced by the new government.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Since February 2012, the government is again led by Janša, and the Secretary-General is again Predalič.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 27 March 2012, the information commissioner reported that the measures for the safeguarding of the recordings were inadequate.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Although the places where the recording device was situated and the recordings were kept were guarded, there were no revision marks on them, which would enable the tracing of their production, usage, viewing and processing.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The law on the protection of personal data was not broken.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] In September 2012, the pre-trial procedure had not been completed yet by the police.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 7 December, the Secretary-General of the Government filed a criminal complaint against the unknown perpetrator and notified about the incident the Criminal Police Directorate and the Office for the Protection of Classified Information.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 8 December, the Slovenian government demanded the removal of the clips from YouTube.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] On 9 December in the evening, when the publication was reported for the first time by media, there were three clips remaining of the allegedly original five although none had been removed by the host.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] YouTube had removed the clips on 15 December 2011, after a copyright-related demand by the Slovenian Computer Emergency Response Team (SI–CERT).
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] However, on the same day they appeared again, albeit shorter.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They were removed again in less than 24 hours.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The clips were republished by users who downloaded them after they have been found by media.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The original perpetrator as well as the uploaders were unknown.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] The decision about the destruction of the original governmental recordings has not been made yet, pending the results of an inspectional surveillance.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] After the incident, the recordings were not produced until 26 January.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] Since then, they have been made only in audio and have been destroyed immediately after extracts had been made.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] They are not transmitted via cable to another building anymore.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] In April 2012, the deputy of the Secretary-General stated that the affair cannot repeat itself, because the government had implemented the traceability of users of governmental session video recordings.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] A tone clip of a closed government session was inadvertently leaked to the website of the Government already on 2 July 2009.
[src:google/2011-slovenian-youtube-incident] It showed Katarina Kresal, the former Minister of the Interior, and Irma Pavlinič Krebs, the former Minister of Public Administration, in a wrangle about the number of the policemen in Slovenia, and had a large echo in the public.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In May 2012, an honour killing took place in Palas Valley, Kohistan, Pakistan.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] It involved the killing of up to five girls, of whom a video had emerged on the internet.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The video featured a boy dancing while four girls clapped and sang along.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] It is claimed that, when the footage became public, a tribal jirga was held shortly afterwards where it was decided that the participants as well as the boy who filmed the video should be killed.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Afzal Kohistani, the elder brother of the two boys involved in the video, went against local tribal tradition and brought the case to national attention; first asking for the participants' protection and subsequently claiming that the girls in the video had already been murdered.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Kohistani campaigned for over seven years to keep the case in the public eye until he was murdered in March 2019.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In September 2019, three men were convicted of murdering three of the girls from the video and were sentenced to life imprisonment, who were later acquitted in October 2023.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The status of the fourth and fifth girl remains unconfirmed.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Four girls − Bazeegha, Sereen Jan, Begum Jan and Amina − are seen clapping and singing; a fifth girl, Shaheen, is also present but does not appear in the video.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In a separate shot, a man is seen dancing, while a second man records both him and the girls.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The video was reportedly filmed at a wedding celebration in the remote and strictly conservative Kohistan region, where cultural traditions are enforced by tribal jirgas in the absence of a capable law enforcement system.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The incident reached national media in June 2012 when Afzal Kohistani, the elder brother of the boys connected to the video, alleged that the girls had been killed on the orders of the Azadkhel tribe jirga.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Officials from the area denied that this had taken place and claimed that the girls were alive.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The case was disposed of after rights activists and government officials made two trips to the remote village to meet the girls, as ordered by the Supreme Court of Pakistan, and initially confirmed that at least four of the girls were alive.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Dr Farzana Bari, a woman's rights activist who made both trips to meet the girls, initially agreed with the conclusions reached but then lodged her dissent.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In response to the closure of the case, Afzal Kohistani asserted that imposters had been presented to the investigation team and that the real girls were dead.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] He filed an application to reopen the case which resulted in three of his brothers being shot dead.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] On 8 February 2014, a former member of the Provincial Assembly of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa from Kohistan, publicly claimed that the four girls seen in the video had been murdered and this prompted Afzal Kohistani to file another petition for the girls to be produced in court.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] After this was rejected, he took it to the Supreme Court where, in November 2016, another commission was ordered.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The defence lawyer argued that the girls couldn't be brought before the commission because of local tribal restrictions making it a matter of honour and shame.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] That argument was rejected by Justice Ejaz Afzal and sessions judge, Shoaib Khan, and other officials, were dispatched to meet the girls.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Four girls duly appeared before them and inconsistences were noted around the age of the girls produced and those who appeared in the video five years prior.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Similar discrepancies were found in each case.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Farzana Bari made a fresh statement to the court reiterating her earlier concerns that the girls seen in the video were not those who had been presented before the commission.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In August 2018, on the order of the Supreme Court, the Kohistan police registered a first information report for the alleged honour killing of the five girls connected to the video.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In December 2018, the investigation found that two out of five victims were reportedly alive and that three of the girls - Siran Jan, Begum Jan and Bazeegha - had, indeed, been killed.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Afzal Kohistani, a Salehkhel tribesman from the Kolai-Palas District, was one of eight children.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The family lived comfortably and were well respected within the village community of Gadaar.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] At various times, Afzal ran a tailoring shop, clerked for a lawyer and traded bee honey, and studied law in his free time.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In 2010, he was living in Mansehra with his wife and two of his younger brothers, Bin Yasir and Gul Nazar.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Around this time, Yasir and Nazar returned to the family village of Gadaar, which is where the video was later filmed.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] When the video went viral Yasir and Nazar were arrested; two of their brothers and other families from the Salehkhel tribe left Gadaar and moved to Allai, where they'd been offered protection from the Azadkhel tribe, to whom the girls in the video belonged.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] As opposed to following the tribal tradition, Afzal tried to prevent the sentence of the jirga from being carried out.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] When that failed he went to the media and repeatedly raised litigation in order to prove that the murders had taken place.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] As a result, three of Afzal's brothers, who stayed behind in Gadaar, were murdered in January 2013 and Afzal's house was firebombed.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] On 6 March 2019, he was shot dead in Abbottabad, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In January 2014, six men from the Azadkhel tribe were convicted of murdering Afzal Kohistani's three brothers.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] One was sentenced to death and five others were sentenced to 25 years in prison, all were relatives of the girls from the video.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] Six other men, including the jirga chief who allegedly ordered the initial murders, were acquitted.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In 2017, the convictions of the six men were overturned by the high court.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] In September 2019, the father of Bazeegha, the father of Sereen Jan and the brother of Begum Jan, were convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison.
[src:google/2012-kohistan-video-case] The three men were later released in October 2023.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The TLD is of interest due to its utility in regards to branding mobile, web, and other applications.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The development of the .app domain name began in 2012 after ICANN announced its "New gTLD Program".
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The program's goal is to expand the current variety of namespaces by an almost unlimited quantity of new entries.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] In January 2012 the program received its first applications and in 2013 first serious investment inflow.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The first part of the program's domain names were released in late 2014.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] On 25 February 2015, Google won the ICANN Auction of Last Resort for the .app gTLD, via their Charleston Road Registry Inc. company, paying US$25 million.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] Google opened public registration of the domain in May 2018.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The name "app" is a short form of the word *application* often used in the IT sector.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] This domain name is to be used by developer companies, professionals and enthusiast developers and entrepreneurs applications, app-support services or other useful related products and tools.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] Because of its potential for use as a domain name space for mobile, web, and other applications—as well as for related products—the .app domain name creation is of interest to many development companies, professionals or enthusiast developers.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] The .app gTLD would allow users to easily recognize a Web site dedicated to an application or related product or service, which has benefits in terms of brandability.
[src:google/app-top-level-domain] .app domains are, according to Gandi.net and other Resellers, "a security-focused space, meaning that HTTPS is required for all websites." This is accomplished by including the .app top-level domain on the HSTS preload list, making HTTPS required on all connections to .app websites.
[src:google/dev] The .dev top-level domain is incorporated on the HSTS preload list, requiring HTTPS on all .dev domains without individual HSTS enlistment.
[src:google/dev] Prior to Google's addition of the .dev TLD to the HSTS preload list, it was common for web developers to create ad hoc addresses ending in .dev on their local networks for testing purposes.
[src:google/dev] These local addresses would be created using either fake DNS servers or their own computer's hosts file and would not be accessible to the wider internet.
[src:google/dev] However, after .dev was added to the HSTS preload list, most modern web browsers began refusing to load .dev websites unless they were served over secure HTTPS connections, thereby causing most of these local testing environments to stop functioning.
[src:google/google-p01] Google was founded in 1998 by American computer scientists Larry Page and Sergey Brin.
[src:google/google-p01] Together, they own about 14% of its publicly listed shares and control 56% of its stockholder voting power through super-voting stock.
[src:google/google-p01] The company went public via an initial public offering (IPO) in 2004.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2015, Google was reorganized as a wholly owned subsidiary of Alphabet Inc.
[src:google/google-p01] Google is Alphabet's largest subsidiary and is a holding company for Alphabet's internet properties and interests.
[src:google/google-p01] Sundar Pichai was appointed CEO of Google in 2015, replacing Larry Page, who became the CEO of Alphabet.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2019, Pichai also became the CEO of Alphabet.
[src:google/google-p01] After the success of its original service, Google Search (often known simply as "Google"), the company has rapidly grown to offer a multitude of products and services.
[src:google/google-p01] Many of these products and services are dominant in their respective industries, as is Google Search.
[src:google/google-p01] Discontinued Google products include gaming (Stadia), Glass, Google+, Reader, Play Music, Nexus, Hangouts, and Inbox by Gmail.
[src:google/google-p01] Google's other ventures outside of internet services and consumer electronics include quantum computing (Willow, Google Quantum AI), self-driving cars (Waymo), and transformer models (Google DeepMind).
[src:google/google-p01] Google Search and YouTube are the two most-visited websites worldwide, followed by Facebook, Instagram, and ChatGPT.
[src:google/google-p01] Google was ranked the second most valuable brand by *Forbes* as of January 2022, and fourth by Interbrand as of February 2022.
[src:google/google-p01] The company has received criticism involving issues such as privacy concerns, tax avoidance, censorship, search neutrality, antitrust, and abuse of its monopoly position.
[src:google/google-p01] Google began in January 1996 as a research project by Larry Page and Sergey Brin while they were both PhD students at Stanford University in California, United States.
[src:google/google-p01] While conventional search engines ranked results by counting how many times the search terms appeared on the page, they theorized about a better system that analyzed the relationships among websites.
[src:google/google-p01] They called this algorithm PageRank; it determined a website's relevance by the number of pages, and the importance of those pages that linked back to the original site.
[src:google/google-p01] Page told his ideas to Hassan, who began writing the code to implement Page's ideas.
[src:google/google-p01] Page and Brin would also use their friend Susan Wojcicki's garage as their office when the search engine was set up in 1998.
[src:google/google-p01] Page and Brin originally nicknamed the new search engine "BackRub" because the system checked backlinks to estimate the importance of a site.
[src:google/google-p01] Hassan, as well as Alan Steremberg were cited by Page and Brin as being critical to the development of Google.
[src:google/google-p01] Rajeev Motwani and Terry Winograd later co-authored with Page and Brin the first paper about the project, describing PageRank and the initial prototype of the Google search engine, published in 1998.
[src:google/google-p01] Héctor García-Molina and Jeffrey Ullman were also cited as contributors to the project.
[src:google/google-p01] PageRank was influenced by a similar page-ranking and site-scoring algorithm earlier used for RankDex, developed by Robin Li in 1996, with Page's PageRank patent including a citation to Li's earlier RankDex patent; Li later went on to create the Chinese search engine Baidu.
[src:google/google-p01] Eventually, they changed the name to *Google*; the name of the search engine was a misspelling of the word *googol*, a very large number written **10100** (1 followed by 100 zeros), picked to signify that the search engine was intended to provide large quantities of information.
[src:google/google-p01] Google was initially funded by an August 1998 investment of $100,000 from Andy Bechtolsheim, co-founder of Sun Microsystems.
[src:google/google-p01] This initial investment served as a motivation to incorporate the company to be able to use the funds.
[src:google/google-p01] Page and Brin initially approached David Cheriton for advice because he had a nearby office in Stanford, and they knew he had startup experience, having recently sold the company he co-founded, Granite Systems, to Cisco for $220 million.
[src:google/google-p01] David arranged a meeting with Page and Brin and his Granite co-founder Andy Bechtolsheim.
[src:google/google-p01] The meeting was set for 8 a.m. at the front porch of David's home in Palo Alto and it had to be brief because Andy had another meeting at Cisco, where he now worked after the acquisition, at 9 a.m.
[src:google/google-p01] Andy briefly tested a demo of the website, liked what he saw, and then went back to his car to grab the check.
[src:google/google-p01] David Cheriton later also joined in with around $200,000 investment.
[src:google/google-p01] Google received money from two other angel investors in 1998, including Amazon founder Jeff Bezos, and entrepreneur Ram Shriram.
[src:google/google-p01] Page and Brin had first approached Shriram, who was a venture capitalist, for funding and counsel, and Shriram invested $250,000 in Google in February 1998.
[src:google/google-p01] Shriram knew Bezos because Amazon had acquired Junglee, at which Shriram was the president.
[src:google/google-p01] It was Shriram who told Bezos about Google.
[src:google/google-p01] Bezos asked Shriram to meet Google's founders and they met six months after Shriram had made his investment when Bezos and his wife were on a vacation trip to the Bay Area.
[src:google/google-p01] Google's initial funding round had already formally closed but Bezos' status as CEO of Amazon was enough to persuade Page and Brin to extend the round and accept his investment.
[src:google/google-p01] Between these initial investors, friends, and family, Google raised around $1,000,000, which is what allowed them to open up their original shop in Menlo Park, California.
[src:google/google-p01] Craig Silverstein, a fellow PhD student at Stanford, was hired as the first employee.
[src:google/google-p01] After some additional small investments through the end of 1998 to early 1999, a new $25 million round of funding was announced on June 7, 1999, with major investors including the venture capital firms Kleiner Perkins and Sequoia Capital.
[src:google/google-p01] Both firms were initially hesitant about investing jointly in Google, as each wanted to retain a larger percentage of control over the company to themselves.
[src:google/google-p01] Page and Brin insisted on taking investments from both.
[src:google/google-p01] Both venture companies finally agreed to investing jointly $12.5 million each due to their belief in Google's great potential and through the mediation of earlier angel investors Ron Conway and Shriram who had contacts in the venture companies.
[src:google/google-p01] In 1998, Page and Brin proposed to sell Google to Yahoo for $1 million, but Yahoo refused.
[src:google/google-p01] A more significant opportunity for Yahoo to acquire Google came in 2002.
[src:google/google-p01] Terry Semel, Yahoo's then-CEO, offered $3 billion to purchase the company, but Page and Brin reportedly held firm on a $5 billion valuation.
[src:google/google-p01] After Yahoo refused to raise its offer, the deal fell through, a move that would later be considered a major strategic misstep for Yahoo.
[src:google/google-p01] In March 1999, the company moved its offices to Palo Alto, California, which is home to several prominent Silicon Valley technology start-ups.
[src:google/google-p01] The next year, Google began selling advertisements associated with search keywords against Page and Brin's initial opposition toward an advertising-funded search engine.
[src:google/google-p01] To maintain an uncluttered page design, advertisements were solely text-based.
[src:google/google-p01] In June 2000, it was announced that Google would become the default search engine provider for Yahoo!, one of the most popular websites at the time, replacing Inktomi.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2001, Google's investors felt the need to have a strong internal management, and they agreed to hire Eric Schmidt as the chairman and CEO of Google.
[src:google/google-p01] Schmidt was proposed by John Doerr from Kleiner Perkins.
[src:google/google-p01] He had been trying to find a CEO that Page and Brin would accept for several months, but they rejected several candidates because they wanted to retain control over the company.
[src:google/google-p01] Michael Moritz from Sequoia Capital at one point even menaced requesting Google to immediately pay back Sequoia's $12.5m investment if they did not fulfill their promise to hire a chief executive officer, which had been made verbally during investment negotiations.
[src:google/google-p01] Schmidt was not initially enthusiastic about joining Google either, as the company's full potential had not yet been widely recognized at the time, and as he was occupied with his responsibilities at Novell where he was CEO.
[src:google/google-p01] As part of him joining, Schmidt agreed to buy $1 million of Google preferred stocks as a way to show his commitment and to provide funds Google needed.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2003, after outgrowing two other locations, the company leased an office complex from Silicon Graphics, at 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway in Mountain View, California.
[src:google/google-p01] The complex became known as the Googleplex, a play on the word googolplex, the number one followed by a googol of zeroes.
[src:google/google-p01] Three years later, Google bought the property from SGI for $319 million.
[src:google/google-p01] By that time, the name "Google" had found its way into everyday language, causing the verb "google" to be added to the *Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary* and the *Oxford English Dictionary*, denoted as: "to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet".
[src:google/google-p01] The first use of the verb on television appeared in an October 2002 episode of *Buffy the Vampire Slayer*.
[src:google/google-p01] On August 19, 2004, Google became a public company via an initial public offering.
[src:google/google-p01] At that time Page, Brin and Schmidt agreed to work together at Google for 20 years, until the year 2024.
[src:google/google-p01] The company opened on the NASDAQ National Market under the five-letter ticker symbol GOOGL with an offering of 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.
[src:google/google-p01] Shares were sold in an online auction format using a system built by Morgan Stanley and Credit Suisse, underwriters for the deal.
[src:google/google-p01] The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a market capitalization of more than $23 billion.
[src:google/google-p01] On October 9, 2006, Google acquired YouTube for $1.65 billion in Google stock.
[src:google/google-p01] On July 20, 2007, Google bid $4.6 billion for the wireless-spectrum auction by the FCC.
[src:google/google-p01] On March 11, 2008, Google acquired DoubleClick for $3.1 billion, transferring to Google valuable relationships that DoubleClick had with Web publishers and advertising agencies.
[src:google/google-p01] By 2011, Google was handling approximately 3 billion searches per day.
[src:google/google-p01] To handle this workload, Google built 11 data centers around the world with several thousand servers in each.
[src:google/google-p01] These data centers allowed Google to handle the ever-changing workload more efficiently.
[src:google/google-p01] In May 2011, the number of monthly unique visitors to Google surpassed one billion for the first time.
[src:google/google-p01] In May 2012, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, in its largest acquisition to date.
[src:google/google-p01] This purchase was made in part to help Google gain Motorola's considerable patent portfolio on mobile phones and wireless technologies, to help protect Google in its ongoing patent disputes with other companies, mainly Apple and Microsoft, and to allow it to continue to freely offer Android.
[src:google/google-p01] In June 2013, Google acquired Waze for $966 million.
[src:google/google-p01] While Waze would remain an independent entity, its social features, such as its crowdsourced location platform, were reportedly valuable integrations between Waze and Google Maps, Google's own mapping service.
[src:google/google-p01] Google announced the launch of a new company, called Calico, on September 19, 2013, to be led by Apple Inc. chairman Arthur Levinson.
[src:google/google-p01] In the official public statement, Page explained that the "health and well-being" company would focus on "the challenge of ageing and associated diseases".
[src:google/google-p01] On January 26, 2014, Google announced it had agreed to acquire DeepMind Technologies, a privately held AI company from London.
[src:google/google-p01] Technology news website *Recode* reported that the company was purchased for $400 million, yet the source of the information was not disclosed.
[src:google/google-p01] A Google spokesperson declined to comment on the price.
[src:google/google-p01] The purchase of DeepMind aids in Google's recent growth in the AI and robotics community.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2015, DeepMind's AlphaGo became the first computer program to defeat a top human pro at the game of Go.
[src:google/google-p01] According to Interbrand's annual Best Global Brands report, Google has been the second most valuable brand in the world (behind Apple Inc.) in 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016, with a valuation of $133 billion.
[src:google/google-p01] On August 10, 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a conglomerate named Alphabet Inc.
[src:google/google-p01] Google became Alphabet's largest subsidiary and the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests.
[src:google/google-p01] Upon completion of the restructuring, Sundar Pichai became CEO of Google, replacing Page, who became CEO of Alphabet.
[src:google/google-p01] Google CEO Sundar Pichai accused Damore of violating company policy by "advancing harmful gender stereotypes in our workplace", and he was fired on the same day.
[src:google/google-p01] On October 25, 2018, *The New York Times* published the *exposé*, "How Google Protected Andy Rubin, the 'Father of Android'".
[src:google/google-p01] The company subsequently announced that "48 employees have been fired over the last two years" for sexual misconduct.
[src:google/google-p01] On November 1, 2018, more than 20,000 Google employees and contractors staged a global walk-out to protest the company's handling of sexual harassment complaints.
[src:google/google-p01] CEO Sundar Pichai was reported to be in support of the protests.
[src:google/google-p01] Later in 2019, some workers accused the company of retaliating against internal activists.
[src:google/google-p01] On March 19, 2019, Google announced that it would enter the video game market, launching a cloud gaming platform called Google Stadia.
[src:google/google-p01] Department of Justice reported that it would investigate Google for antitrust violations.
[src:google/google-p01] This led to the filing of an antitrust lawsuit in October 2020, on the grounds the company had abused a monopoly position in the search and search advertising markets.
[src:google/google-p01] In December 2019, former PayPal chief operating officer Bill Ready became Google's new commerce chief.
[src:google/google-p01] Ready's role will not be directly involved with Google Pay.
[src:google/google-p01] In April 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Google announced several cost-cutting measures.
[src:google/google-p01] These measures included slowing down hiring for the remainder of 2020, except for a small number of strategic areas, recalibrating the focus and pace of investments in areas like data centers and machines, and non-business essential marketing and travel.
[src:google/google-p01] The 2020 Google services outages disrupted Google services: one in August that affected Google Drive among others, another in November affecting YouTube, and a third in December affecting the entire suite of Google applications.
[src:google/google-p01] All three outages were resolved within hours.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2021, the Alphabet Workers Union was founded, composed mostly of Google employees.
[src:google/google-p01] In January 2021, the Australian Government proposed legislation that would require Google and Facebook to pay media companies for the right to use their content.
[src:google/google-p01] In response, Google threatened to close off access to its search engine in Australia.
[src:google/google-p01] In March 2021, Google reportedly paid $20 million for Ubisoft ports on Google Stadia.
[src:google/google-p01] Google spent "tens of millions of dollars" on getting major publishers such as Ubisoft and Take-Two to bring some of their biggest games to Stadia.
[src:google/google-p01] In April 2021, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Google ran a years-long program called "Project Bernanke" that used data from past advertising bids to gain an advantage over competing for ad services.
[src:google/google-p01] This was revealed in documents concerning the antitrust lawsuit filed by ten US states against Google in December.
[src:google/google-p01] In September 2021, the Australian government announced plans to curb Google's capability to sell targeted ads, claiming that the company has a monopoly on the market harming publishers, advertisers, and consumers.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2022, Google began accepting requests for the removal of phone numbers, physical addresses and email addresses from its search results.
[src:google/google-p01] It had previously accepted requests for removing confidential data only, such as Social Security numbers, bank account and credit card numbers, personal signatures, and medical records.
[src:google/google-p01] Even with the new policy, Google may remove information from only certain but not all search queries.
[src:google/google-p01] It would not remove content that is "broadly useful", such as news articles, or already part of the public record.
[src:google/google-p01] In May 2022, Google announced that the company had acquired California based, MicroLED display technology development and manufacturing Start-up company Raxium.
[src:google/google-p01] Raxium is set to join Google's Devices and Services team to aid in the development of micro-optics, monolithic integration, and system integration.
[src:google/google-p01] In December 2022, Google debuted OSV-Scanner, a Go tool for finding security holes in open source software, which pulls from the largest open source vulnerability database of its kind to defend against supply chain attacks.
[src:google/google-p01] Following the success of ChatGPT and concerns that Google was falling behind in the AI race, Google's senior management issued a "code red" and a "directive that all of its most important products—those with more than a billion users—must incorporate generative AI within months".
[src:google/google-p01] In March 2023, in direct response to the rapid rise of ChatGPT, Google released Bard (now Gemini), a generative artificial intelligence chatbot.
[src:google/google-p01] In early May 2023, Google announced its plans to build two additional data centers in Ohio.
[src:google/google-p01] These centers, which will be built in Columbus and Lancaster, will power up the company's tools, including AI technology.
[src:google/google-p01] The said data hub will add to the already operational center near Columbus, bringing Google's total investment in Ohio to over $2 billion.
[src:google/google-p01] In August 2024, Google would lose a lawsuit which started in 2020 in lower court, as it was found that the company had an illegal monopoly over Internet search.
[src:google/google-p01] Circuit Court Judge Amit Mehta held that this monopoly was in violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act.
[src:google/google-p01] In September 2024, the Court of Justice of the European Union (EU), based in Luxembourg, also found that Google held an illegal monopoly, in this case with regards to its shopping search, and could not avoid paying a €2.4 billion fine.
[src:google/google-p01] The EU Court of Justice found that Google's treatment of rival shopping searches, which the court referred to as "discriminatory", was in violation of the Digital Markets Act.
[src:google/google-p01] In October 2024, Google was fined by a local Russian court a symbolic 2.5 decillion dollars for allegedly blocking pro-Kremlin propaganda.
[src:google/google-p01] In November 2024, Google announced the establishment of a new AI hub in Saudi Arabia, aiming to support the Kingdom's economic growth and technological development as part of its Vision 2030 initiative.
[src:google/google-p01] This AI hub is projected to contribute up to $71 billion to Saudi Arabia's economy by advancing AI-driven solutions tailored to the region's specific needs and training local talent.
[src:google/google-p01] The partnership between Google and Saudi Arabia includes collaboration with key stakeholders, such as the Public Investment Fund (PIF), to develop AI applications that will benefit sectors like healthcare, finance, oil and gas, and logistics.
[src:google/google-p01] The initiative focuses on creating localized AI technologies, with an emphasis on integrating Arabic language capabilities and enabling widespread cloud adoption.
[src:google/google-p01] In March 2025, Google agreed to acquire Wiz, a New York-based cybersecurity startup focusing on cloud computing, for US$32 billion.
[src:google/google-p01] This cash deal would be Google's biggest ever, as well as it currently being the most expensive deal of 2025.
[src:google/google-p01] Alphabet reportedly tried to close a deal for only $23 billion in 2024, but this fell apart after concerns about regulatory hurdles, among other issues.
[src:google/google-p01] Wiz, a company located in the U.S. and Israel, was cofounded in 2020 by Assaf Rappaport.
[src:google/google-p01] The company is backed by a number of Silicon Valley venture capitalists, as well as notably being partnered with Amazon and Microsoft, as listed in their website.
[src:google/google-p01] Department of Defense announced that Google had received a $200 million contract for AI in the military, along with Anthropic, OpenAI, and xAI.
[src:google/google-p01] In March 2026, Google signed an energy pledge at the White House which required them to bear the cost of new electricity generation to power their data centers.
[src:google/google-p01] Google indexes billions of web pages to allow users to search for the information they desire through the use of keywords and operators.
[src:google/google-p01] According to comScore market research from November 2009, Google Search is the dominant search engine in the United States market, with a market share of 65.6%.
[src:google/google-p01] In May 2017, Google enabled a new "Personal" tab in Google Search, letting users search for content in their Google accounts' various services, including email messages from Gmail and photos from Google Photos.
[src:google/google-p01] Google launched its Google News service in 2002, an automated service which summarizes news articles from various websites.
[src:google/google-p01] Google also hosts Google Books, which allows users to search books in its database and shows limited previews, or the full book when allowed.
[src:google/google-p01] Google expanded its search services to include shopping (launched originally as Froogle in 2002), finance (launched 2006), and flights (launched 2011).
[src:google/google-p01] Google generates most of its revenues from advertising.
[src:google/google-p01] This includes sales of apps, purchases made in-app, digital content products on Google and YouTube, Android and licensing and service fees, including fees received for Google Cloud offerings.
[src:google/google-p01] Forty-six percent of this profit was from clicks (cost per clicks), amounting to US$109,652 million in 2017.
[src:google/google-p01] This includes three principal methods, namely AdMob, AdSense (such as AdSense for Content, AdSense for Search, etc.) and DoubleClick AdExchange.
[src:google/google-p01] In addition to its own algorithms for understanding search requests, Google uses technology from its acquisition of DoubleClick, to project user interest and target advertising to the search context and the user history.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2007, Google launched "AdSense for Mobile", taking advantage of the emerging mobile advertising market.
[src:google/google-p01] Google Analytics allows website owners to track where and how people use their website, for example by examining click rates for all the links on a page.
[src:google/google-p01] Google advertisements can be placed on third-party websites in a two-part program.
[src:google/google-p01] Google Ads allows advertisers to display their advertisements in the Google content network, through a cost-per-click scheme.
[src:google/google-p01] The sister service, Google AdSense, allows website owners to display these advertisements on their website and earn money every time ads are clicked.
[src:google/google-p01] One of the criticisms of this program is the possibility of click fraud, which occurs when a person or automated script clicks on advertisements without being interested in the product, causing the advertiser to pay money to Google unduly.
[src:google/google-p01] Industry reports in 2006 claimed that approximately 14 to 20 percent of clicks were fraudulent or invalid.
[src:google/google-p01] Google Search Console (rebranded from Google Webmaster Tools in May 2015) allows webmasters to check the sitemap, crawl rate, and for security issues of their websites, as well as optimize their website's visibility.
[src:google/google-p01] Google had previously used virtual assistants and chatbots, such as Google Bard, prior to the announcement of Gemini in March 2024.
[src:google/google-p01] None of them had been seen as legitimate competitors to ChatGPT, unlike Gemini.
[src:google/google-p01] An AI training program for Google employees was also introduced in April 2024.
[src:google/google-p01] Google has created the text-to-image model Imagen, and the text-to-video model Veo.
[src:google/google-p01] Google integrated AI Overviews into Google Search, and added an AI mode where the search results page is AI-generated.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2025, Google announced SynthID Detector, a tool that uses watermarking to identify whether content such as text, images, audio, or video was generated using Google products.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2023, Google released NotebookLM, an online tool for synthesizing documents using Gemini.
[src:google/google-p01] In September 2024, it gained attention for its "Audio Overview" feature, which generates podcast-like summaries of documents.
[src:google/google-p01] Google also developed LearnLM, a family of language models serving as personal AI tutors.
[src:google/google-p01] In June 2026, UK regulators instructed Google to give publishers the ability to choose how their content is used and resurfaced in its AI-generated snippets.
[src:google/google-p01] A job search product has also existed since before 2017, Google for Jobs is an enhanced search feature that aggregates listings from job boards and career sites.
[src:google/google-p01] Google Earth, launched in 2005, allows users to see high-definition satellite pictures from all over the world for free through a client software downloaded to their computers.
[src:google/google-p01] Google develops the Android mobile operating system, as well as its smartwatch, television, car, and Internet of things-enabled smart devices variations.
[src:google/google-p01] It also develops the Google Chrome web browser, ChromeOS, an operating system based on Chrome, and the AI-powered integrated development environment Google Antigravity.
[src:google/google-p01] In January 2010, Google released Nexus One, the first Android phone under its own brand.
[src:google/google-p01] It spawned a number of phones and tablets under the "Nexus" branding until its eventual discontinuation in 2016, replaced by a new brand called Pixel.
[src:google/google-p01] In 2011, the Chromebook was introduced, which runs on ChromeOS.
[src:google/google-p01] In July 2013, Google introduced the Chromecast dongle, which allows users to stream content from their smartphones to televisions.
[src:google/google-p01] In June 2014, Google announced Google Cardboard, a simple cardboard viewer that lets the user place their smartphone in a special front compartment to view virtual reality (VR) media.
[src:google/google-p01] In October 2016, Google announced Daydream View, a lightweight VR viewer which lets the user place their smartphone in the front hinge to view VR media.
[src:google/google-p01] On September 24, 2012, Google launched Google for Entrepreneurs, a largely not-for-profit business incubator providing startups with co-working spaces known as Campuses, with assistance to startup founders that may include workshops, conferences, and mentorships.
[src:google/google-p01] There are seven Campus locations: Berlin, London, Madrid, Seoul, São Paulo, Tel Aviv, and Warsaw.
[src:google/google-p01] On March 15, 2016, Google announced the introduction of Google Analytics 360 Suite, "a set of integrated data and marketing analytics products, designed specifically for the needs of enterprise-class marketers" which can be integrated with BigQuery on the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:google/google-p01] Among other things, the suite is designed to help "enterprise class marketers" "see the complete customer journey", generate "useful insights", and "deliver engaging experiences to the right people".
[src:google/google-p01] Jack Marshall of *The Wall Street Journal* wrote that the suite competes with existing marketing cloud offerings by companies including Adobe, Oracle, Salesforce, and IBM.
[src:google/google-p01] In February 2010, Google announced the Google Fiber project, with experimental plans to build an ultra-high-speed broadband network for 50,000 to 500,000 customers in one or more American cities.
[src:google/google-p01] Following Google's corporate restructure to make Alphabet Inc. its parent company, Google Fiber was moved to Alphabet's Access division.
[src:google/google-p01] In April 2015, Google announced Project Fi, a mobile virtual network operator, that combines Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different telecommunication providers in an effort to enable seamless connectivity and fast Internet signal.
[src:google/google-p01] In August 2023, Google became the first major tech company to join the OpenWallet Foundation, launched earlier in the year, whose goal was creating open-source software for interoperable digital wallets.
[src:google/google-p02] From the financial year of 2015, figures are published for Alphabet Inc.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's initial public offering (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004.
[src:google/google-p02] At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.
[src:google/google-p02] The stock performed well after the IPO, with shares hitting $350 for the first time on October 31, 2007, primarily because of strong sales and earnings in the online advertising market.
[src:google/google-p02] The surge in stock price was fueled mainly by individual investors, as opposed to large institutional investors and mutual funds.
[src:google/google-p02] GOOG shares split into GOOG class C shares and GOOGL class A shares.
[src:google/google-p02] Since the fourth quarter of 2015, Google's stock has been traded under its holding company, Alphabet Inc., under the ticker symbols GOOGL and GOOG, and on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol GGQ1.
[src:google/google-p02] In the third quarter of 2005, Google reported a 700% increase in profit, largely due to large companies shifting their advertising strategies from newspapers, magazines, and television to the Internet.
[src:google/google-p02] For the 2006 fiscal year, the company reported $10.492 billion in total advertising revenues and only $112 million in licensing and other revenues.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2011, 96% of Google's revenue was derived from its advertising programs.
[src:google/google-p02] Google generated $50 billion in annual revenue for the first time in 2012, generating $38 billion the previous year.
[src:google/google-p02] In January 2013, then-CEO Larry Page commented, "We ended 2012 with a strong quarter ...
[src:google/google-p02] Revenues were up 36% year-on-year, and 8% quarter-on-quarter.
[src:google/google-p02] And we hit $50 billion in revenues for the first time last year – not a bad achievement in just a decade and a half." Google's consolidated revenue for the third quarter of 2013 was reported in mid-October 2013 as $14.89 billion, a 12 percent increase compared to the previous quarter.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's Internet business was responsible for $10.8 billion of this total, with an increase in the number of users' clicks on advertisements.
[src:google/google-p02] By January 2014, Google's market capitalization had grown to $397 billion.
[src:google/google-p02] Google uses various tax avoidance strategies.
[src:google/google-p02] On the list of largest technology companies by revenue, it pays the lowest taxes to the countries of origin of its revenues.
[src:google/google-p02] Google saved $3.1 billion between 2007 and 2010 in taxes by shuttling non-U.S. profits through Ireland and the Netherlands and then to Bermuda.
[src:google/google-p02] Such techniques lower its non-U.S. tax rate to 2.3 per cent, while normally the corporate tax rate in, for instance, the UK is 28 per cent.
[src:google/google-p02] This reportedly sparked a French investigation into Google's transfer pricing practices in 2012.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2020, Google said it had overhauled its controversial global tax structure and consolidated all of its intellectual property holdings back to the U.S.
[src:google/google-p02] Google Vice-president Matt Brittin testified to the Public Accounts Committee of the UK House of Commons that his UK sales team made no sales and hence owed no sales taxes to the UK.
[src:google/google-p02] In January 2016, Google reached a settlement with the UK to pay £130m in back taxes plus higher taxes in future.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2017, Google channeled $22.7 billion from the Netherlands to Bermuda to reduce its tax bill.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2013, Google ranked 5th in lobbying spending, up from 213th in 2003.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2012, the company ranked 2nd in campaign donations of technology and Internet sections.
[src:google/google-p02] The name "Google" originated from a misspelling of "googol", which refers to the number represented by a 1 followed by one-hundred zeros.
[src:google/google-p02] In October 2015, a related motto was adopted in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase: "Do the right thing".
[src:google/google-p02] The original motto was retained in the code of conduct of Google, now a subsidiary of Alphabet.
[src:google/google-p02] The original Google logo was designed by Sergey Brin.
[src:google/google-p02] Since 1998, Google has been designing special, temporary alternate logos to place on their homepage intended to celebrate holidays, events, achievements and people.
[src:google/google-p02] The first Google Doodle was in honor of the Burning Man Festival of 1998.
[src:google/google-p02] The doodle was designed by Larry Page and Sergey Brin to notify users of their absence in case the servers crashed.
[src:google/google-p02] Subsequent Google Doodles were designed by an outside contractor, until Larry and Sergey asked then-intern Dennis Hwang to design a logo for Bastille Day in 2000.
[src:google/google-p02] From that point onward, Doodles have been organized and created by a team of employees termed "Doodlers".
[src:google/google-p02] Google has a tradition of creating April Fools' Day jokes.
[src:google/google-p02] Its first on April 1, 2000, was Google MentalPlex which allegedly featured the use of mental power to search the web.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2007, Google announced a free Internet service called TiSP, or Toilet Internet Service Provider, where one obtained a connection by flushing one end of a fiber-optic cable down their toilet.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's services contain easter eggs, such as the Swedish Chef's "Bork bork bork", Pig Latin, "Hacker" or leetspeak, Elmer Fudd, Pirate, and Klingon as language selections for its search engine.
[src:google/google-p02] On *Fortune* magazine's list of the best companies to work for, Google ranked first in 2007, 2008 and 2012, and fourth in 2009 and 2010.
[src:google/google-p02] Google was also nominated in 2010 to be the world's most attractive employer to graduating students in the Universum Communications talent attraction index.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's corporate philosophy includes principles such as "you can make money without doing evil", "you can be serious without a suit", and "work should be challenging and the challenge should be fun".
[src:google/google-p02] As of September 30, 2020, Alphabet Inc. had 132,121 employees, of which more than 100,000 worked for Google.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's 2020 diversity report states that 32 percent of its workforce are women and 68 percent are men, with the ethnicity of its workforce being predominantly white (51.7%) and Asian (41.9%).
[src:google/google-p02] Within tech roles, 23.6 percent were women; and 26.7 percent of leadership roles were held by women.
[src:google/google-p02] In addition to its 100,000+ full-time employees, Google used about 121,000 temporary workers and contractors, as of March 2019.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's employees are hired based on a hierarchical system.
[src:google/google-p02] Employees are split into six hierarchies based on experience and can range "from entry-level data center workers at level one to managers and experienced engineers at level six".
[src:google/google-p02] As a motivation technique, Google uses a policy known as Innovation Time Off, where Google engineers are encouraged to spend 20% of their work time on projects that interest them.
[src:google/google-p02] Some of Google's services, such as Gmail, Google News, Orkut, and AdSense, originated from these independent endeavors.
[src:google/google-p02] In a talk at Stanford University, Marissa Mayer, Google's vice-president of Search Products and User Experience until July 2012, showed that half of all new product launches in the second half of 2005 had originated from the Innovation Time Off.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2005, articles in *The New York Times* and other sources began suggesting that Google had lost its anti-corporate, no evil philosophy.
[src:google/google-p02] In an effort to maintain the company's unique culture, Google designated a Chief Culture Officer whose purpose was to develop and maintain the culture and work on ways to keep true to the core values that the company was founded on.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has also faced allegations of sexism and ageism from former employees.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2013, a class action against several Silicon Valley companies, including Google, was filed for alleged "no cold call" agreements which restrained the recruitment of high-tech employees.
[src:google/google-p02] In a lawsuit filed January 8, 2018, multiple employees and job applicants alleged Google discriminated against a class defined by their "conservative political views[,] male gender[,] and/or ...
[src:google/google-p02] On January 25, 2020, the formation of an international workers union of Google employees, Alpha Global, was announced.
[src:google/google-p02] The coalition is made up of "13 different unions representing workers in 10 countries, including the United States, [the] United Kingdom, and Switzerland".
[src:google/google-p02] The group is affiliated with the UNI Global Union, which represents nearly 20 million international workers from various unions and federations.
[src:google/google-p02] The formation of the union is in response to persistent allegations of mistreatment of Google employees and a toxic workplace culture.
[src:google/google-p02] Google had previously been accused of surveilling and firing employees who were suspected of organizing a workers union.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2021, court documents revealed that between 2018 and 2020, Google ran an anti-union campaign called Project Vivian to "convince them (employees) that unions suck".
[src:google/google-p02] In February 2025, Google dropped their commitment to make "diversity, equity, and inclusion [DEI] part of everything we do" from their annual investor report.
[src:google/google-p02] This action followed Meta, Amazon, Pepsi, McDonald's, Walmart, and others who all have rolled back their DEI programmes.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's headquarters in Mountain View, California is referred to as "the Googleplex", a play on words on the number googolplex and the headquarters itself being a *complex* of buildings.
[src:google/google-p02] Internationally, Google has over 78 offices in more than 50 countries.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2006, Google moved into about 300,000 square feet (27,900 m2) of office space at 111 Eighth Avenue in Manhattan, New York City.
[src:google/google-p02] The office houses its largest advertising sales team.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2010, Google bought the building housing the headquarters, in a deal that valued the property at around $1.9 billion.
[src:google/google-p02] In March 2018, Google's parent company Alphabet bought the nearby Chelsea Market building for $2.4 billion.
[src:google/google-p02] The sale is touted as one of the most expensive real estate transactions for a single building in the history of New York.
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2018, Google announced its plan to expand its New York City office to a capacity of 12,000 employees.
[src:google/google-p02] The same December, it was announced that a $1 billion, 1,700,000-square-foot (160,000 m2) headquarters for Google would be built in Manhattan's Hudson Square neighborhood.
[src:google/google-p02] Called Google Hudson Square, the new campus is projected to more than double the number of Google employees working in New York City.
[src:google/google-p02] By late 2006, Google established a new headquarters for its AdWords division in Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2006, Google opened offices on Carnegie Mellon's campus in Pittsburgh, focusing on shopping-related advertisement coding and smartphone applications and programs.
[src:google/google-p02] Other office locations in the U.S. include Atlanta; Austin; Boulder, Colorado; Cambridge, Massachusetts; San Francisco; Seattle and Kirkland, Washington; Birmingham, Michigan; Reston, Virginia, Washington, D.C., and Madison, Wisconsin.
[src:google/google-p02] It also has product research and development operations in cities around the world, namely Sydney (birthplace location of Google Maps) and London (part of Android development).
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2013, Google announced plans for a new London headquarter, a 1 million square foot office able to accommodate 4,500 employees.
[src:google/google-p02] Recognized as one of the biggest ever commercial property acquisitions at the time of the deal's announcement in January, Google submitted plans for the new headquarter to the Camden Council in June 2017.
[src:google/google-p02] In May 2015, Google announced its intention to create its own campus in Hyderabad, India.
[src:google/google-p02] The new campus, reported to be the company's largest outside the United States, will accommodate 13,000 employees.
[src:google/google-p02] In September 2025 Google opened their £735m AI Centre in Waltham Cross, Hertfordshire and announced their plans for £5 bn investment in AI research, in the same month that Alphabet reached market capitalisation of $3 trillion.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's Global Offices sum a total of 86 locations worldwide, with 32 offices in North America, three of them in Canada and 29 in the United States, California being the state with the most Google's offices with 9 in total including the Googleplex.
[src:google/google-p02] Google counts 6 offices in the Latin America region and 24 in Europe, 3 of them in United Kingdom.
[src:google/google-p02] The Asia-Pacific region counts with 26 offices principally five in India and three in Australia, and three in China, while the Africa and Middle East region counts five offices.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has data centers in North and South America, Asia, and Europe.
[src:google/google-p02] There is no official data on the number of servers in Google data centers; however, research and advisory firm Gartner estimated in a July 2016 report that Google at the time had 2.5 million servers.
[src:google/google-p02] Traditionally, Google relied on parallel computing on commodity hardware like mainstream x86 computers (similar to home PCs) to keep costs per query low.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2005, it started developing its own designs, which were only revealed in 2009.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has built its own private submarine communications cables.
[src:google/google-p02] The first cable, named Curie, connects California with Chile and was completed on November 15, 2019.
[src:google/google-p02] The second fully Google-owned undersea cable, named Dunant, connects the United States with France and is planned to begin operation in 2020.
[src:google/google-p02] Google's third subsea cable, Equiano, will connect Lisbon (Portugal) with Lagos (Nigeria) and Cape Town (South Africa).
[src:google/google-p02] The company's fourth cable, named Grace Hopper, connects landing points in New York (US), Bude (UK) and Bilbao (Spain), and is expected to become operational in 2022.
[src:google/google-p02] In October 2006, the company announced plans to install thousands of solar panels on its Mountain View campus to provide up to 1.6 Megawatt of electricity, enough to satisfy approximately 30% of the campus' energy needs.
[src:google/google-p02] The system is the largest rooftop photovoltaic power station constructed on a U.S. corporate campus and one of the largest on any corporate site in the world.
[src:google/google-p02] Since 2007, Google has aimed for carbon neutrality in regard to its operations.
[src:google/google-p02] In Spring 2009, Google hired a herd of 200 goats for a week from California Grazing to mow their lawn.
[src:google/google-p02] Google disclosed in September 2011 that it "continuously uses enough electricity to power 200,000 homes", almost 260 million watts or about a quarter of the output of a nuclear power plant.
[src:google/google-p02] Total carbon emissions for 2010 were just under 1.5 million metric tons, mostly due to fossil fuels that provide electricity for the data centers.
[src:google/google-p02] Google said that 25 percent of its energy was supplied by renewable fuels in 2010.
[src:google/google-p02] An average search uses only 0.3 watt-hours of electricity, so all global searches are only 12.5 million watts or 5% of the total electricity consumption by Google.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2010, Google Energy made its first investment in a renewable energy project, putting $38.8 million into two wind farms in North Dakota.
[src:google/google-p02] The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5 megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes.
[src:google/google-p02] In February 2010, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.
[src:google/google-p02] The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.
[src:google/google-p02] In July 2010, Google signed an agreement with an Iowa wind farm to buy 114 megawatts of power for 20 years.
[src:google/google-p02] In December 2016, Google announced that—starting in 2017—it would purchase enough renewable energy to match 100% of the energy usage of its data centers and offices.
[src:google/google-p02] The commitment will make Google "the world's largest corporate buyer of renewable power, with commitments reaching 2.6 gigawatts (2,600 megawatts) of wind and solar energy".
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2017, Google bought 536 megawatts of wind power.
[src:google/google-p02] The purchase made the firm reach 100% renewable energy.
[src:google/google-p02] The wind energy comes from two power plants in South Dakota, one in Iowa and one in Oklahoma.
[src:google/google-p02] In September 2019, Google's chief executive announced plans for a $2 billion wind and solar investment, the biggest renewable energy deal in corporate history.
[src:google/google-p02] This will grow their green energy profile by 40%, giving them an extra 1.6 gigawatt of clean energy, the company said.
[src:google/google-p02] In September 2020, Google announced it had retroactively offset all of its carbon emissions since the company's foundation in 1998.
[src:google/google-p02] It also stated that it is committed to operating its data centers and offices using only carbon-free energy by 2030.
[src:google/google-p02] In October 2020, the company pledged to make the packaging for its hardware products 100% plastic-free and 100% recyclable by 2025.
[src:google/google-p02] It also said that all its final assembly manufacturing sites will achieve a UL 2799 Zero Waste to Landfill certification by 2022 by ensuring that the vast majority of waste from the manufacturing process is recycled instead of ending up in a landfill.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2023 Google consumed 24 TWh of electricity, more than countries such as Iceland, Ghana, the Dominican Republic, or Tunisia.
[src:google/google-p02] Google donates to climate change denial political groups including the State Policy Network and the Competitive Enterprise Institute.
[src:google/google-p02] The company also actively funds and profits from climate disinformation by monetizing ad spaces on most of the largest climate disinformation sites.
[src:google/google-p02] Google continued to monetize and profit from sites propagating climate disinformation even after the company updated their policy to prohibit placing their ads on similar sites.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2004, Google formed the not-for-profit philanthropic Google.org, with a start-up fund of $1 billion.
[src:google/google-p02] The mission of the organization is to create awareness about climate change, global public health, and global poverty.
[src:google/google-p02] One of its first projects was to develop a viable plug-in hybrid electric vehicle that can attain 100 miles per gallon.
[src:google/google-p02] Google hired Larry Brilliant as the program's executive director in 2004 and Megan Smith has since replaced him as director.
[src:google/google-p02] In March 2007, in partnership with the Mathematical Sciences Research Institute (MSRI), Google hosted the first Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival at its headquarters in Mountain View.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2011, Google donated €1 million to International Mathematical Olympiad to support the next five annual International Mathematical Olympiads (2011–2015).
[src:google/google-p02] In July 2012, Google launched a "Legalize Love" campaign in support of gay rights.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2008, Google announced its "project 10100", which accepted ideas for how to help the community and then allowed Google users to vote on their favorites.
[src:google/google-p02] Responding to the humanitarian crisis after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Google announced a $15 million donation to support Ukrainian citizens.
[src:google/google-p02] The company also decided to transform its office in Warsaw into a help center for refugees.
[src:google/google-p02] Also in February 2022, Google announced a $100 million fund to expand skills training and job placement for low-income Americans, in conjunction with non-profits Year Up, Social Finance, and Merit America.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2025, Google was one of the donors who funded the White House's East Wing demolition, and planned building of a ballroom.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has had criticism over issues such as aggressive tax avoidance, search neutrality, copyright, censorship of search results and content, and privacy.
[src:google/google-p02] In a 2022 National Labor Relations Board ruling, court documents suggested that Google sponsored a secretive project—*Project Vivian*—to counsel its employees and to discourage them from forming unions.
[src:google/google-p02] On May 1, 2023, Google placed an ad against the Brazilian Congressional Bill No.
[src:google/google-p02] 2630, an anti-disinformation law that was about to be approved, on its search homepage in Brazil, calling on its users to ask congressional representatives to oppose the legislation.
[src:google/google-p02] The company then promptly removed the ad.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has a US$1.2 billion artificial intelligence and surveillance contract with the Israeli military known as Project Nimbus.
[src:google/google-p02] According to Google employees, the Israeli military could use this technology to expand its surveillance of Palestinians living in the occupied territories.
[src:google/google-p02] Google relocated an outspoken employee overseas, and the employee claimed it was a "retaliation for publicly criticizing the contract".
[src:google/google-p02] Other Palestinian employees have described an "institutionalised bias" within the company.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2021, Google and Amazon engaged in negotiations for a substantial cloud computing agreement valued at $1.2 billion, during which Israel insisted on the inclusion of a confidential code referred to as the "blink mechanism".
[src:google/google-p02] This stipulation compelled Google and Amazon to essentially disregard legal responsibilities in various nations.
[src:google/google-p02] Israel expressed apprehension that the data transferred to the cloud services of these global corporations might be accessible to foreign law enforcement agencies.
[src:google/google-p02] As per documents disclosed to The Guardian, both Google and Amazon consented to the blink mechanism in order to finalize the profitable agreement.
[src:google/google-p02] During 2025, Google engaged in a $45 million, six-month contract with Israel to run advertising campaigns.
[src:google/google-p02] Some Youtube ads aimed to cast doubt on the existence of a famine in Gaza.
[src:google/google-p02] Many complaints were filed against Israel's videos, but Google maintained that the ads did not violate its content policies.
[src:google/google-p02] On October 31, 2024, the Russian government imposed a "symbolic" fine of $20 decillion on Google for blocking pro-Russian YouTube channels.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2022, during the invasion of Ukraine, a Russian court had ordered Google to restore the channels, with penalties doubling every week according to TASS.
[src:google/google-p02] This comes alongside other large fines against social media companies accused of hosting content critical of the Kremlin or supportive of Ukraine.
[src:google/google-p02] In July 2018, Mozilla program manager Chris Peterson accused Google of intentionally slowing down YouTube performance on Firefox.
[src:google/google-p02] In April 2019, former Mozilla executive Jonathan Nightingale accused Google of intentionally and systematically sabotaging the Firefox browser over the past decade in order to boost adoption of Google Chrome.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2019, a hub for critics of Google dedicated to abstaining from using Google products coalesced in the Reddit online community /r/degoogle.
[src:google/google-p02] The DeGoogle grassroots campaign continues to grow as privacy activists highlight information about Google products, and the associated incursion on personal privacy rights by the company.
[src:google/google-p02] Google reportedly paid Apple $22 billion in 2022 to maintain its position as the default search engine on Safari.
[src:google/google-p02] It marks one of the largest payments between two tech giants in recent years.
[src:google/google-p02] On June 27, 2017, the company received a record fine of €2.42 billion from the European Union (EU) for "promoting its own shopping comparison service at the top of search results".
[src:google/google-p02] On July 18, 2018, the European Commissioner for Competition fined Google €4.34 billion for breaching European Union competition law.
[src:google/google-p02] The abuse of dominants position has been referred to as Google's constraint applied to Android device manufacturers and network operators to ensure that traffic on Android devices goes to the Google search engine.
[src:google/google-p02] On October 9, 2018, Google confirmed that it had appealed the fine to the General Court of the EU.
[src:google/google-p02] On March 20, 2019, the European Commission imposed a €1.49 billion ($1.69 billion) fine on Google for preventing rivals from being able to "compete and innovate fairly" in the online advertising market.
[src:google/google-p02] EU competition commissioner Margrethe Vestager said Google had violated EU antitrust rules by "imposing anti-competitive contractual restrictions on third-party websites" that required them to exclude search results from Google's rivals.
[src:google/google-p02] On September 14, 2022, Google lost the appeal of a €4.125 billion (£3.5 billion) fine, which was ruled to be paid after it was proved by the European Commission that Google forced Android phone-makers to carry Google's search and web browser apps.
[src:google/google-p02] Since the initial accusations, Google has changed its policy.
[src:google/google-p02] On July 2, 2026, the Court of Justice of the European Union dismissed Google's appeal, upholding the fine of around €4.1 billion for abusing its dominant position in relation to the Android operating system.
[src:google/google-p02] In March 2024, a former Google software engineer and Chinese national named Linwei Ding was accused of stealing confidential artificial intelligence information from the company and handing it to Chinese corporations.
[src:google/google-p02] Ding had allegedly stolen over 500 files from the company over the course of 5 years, having been hired in 2019.
[src:google/google-p02] Upon discovering Ding had been in contact with Chinese state-owned companies, Google notified the FBI, who carried on the investigation of the data breach.
[src:google/google-p02] On September 10, 2024, Europe's top court imposed a €2.4 billion fine on Google for abusing its dominance in the shopping comparison market, marking the conclusion of a case that began in 2009 with a complaint from British firm Foundem.
[src:google/google-p02] On September 18, 2024, Alphabet's Google won a €1.49 billion ($1.7 billion) antitrust fine from the EU, while Qualcomm's efforts to repeal a penalty were unsuccessful.
[src:google/google-p02] The General Court agreed with many of the European Commission's findings but annulled the Google fine, stating that the Commission failed to consider all relevant factors and did not demonstrate harm to innovation or consumers.
[src:google/google-p02] Google noted that it had already changed its contract practices in 2016.
[src:google/google-p02] Meanwhile, Qualcomm saw its fine reduced slightly but failed to overturn the ruling regarding its predatory pricing against Icera.
[src:google/google-p02] Both companies have options to appeal further.
[src:google/google-p02] On September 5, 2025, the European Commission fined Google €2.95 billion ($3.47 billion), for breaching EU antitrust rules.
[src:google/google-p02] Regulators say Google abused its dominance by giving preferential treatment to its ad exchange within its publisher ad server and ad-buying tools.
[src:google/google-p02] Congressional hearings in July 2020, and a report from the U.S.
[src:google/google-p02] House of Representatives' Antitrust Subcommittee released in early October, the U.S.
[src:google/google-p02] Department of Justice filed an antitrust lawsuit against Google on October 20, 2020, asserting that it has illegally maintained its monopoly position in web search and search advertising.
[src:google/google-p02] The lawsuit alleged that Google engaged in anticompetitive behavior by paying Apple between $8 billion and $12 billion to be the default search engine on iPhones.
[src:google/google-p02] Later that month, both Facebook and Alphabet agreed to "cooperate and assist one another" in the face of investigation into their online advertising practices.
[src:google/google-p02] Another suit was brought against Google in 2023 for illegally monopolizing the advertising technology market.
[src:google/google-p02] In August 2024, District of Columbia U.S.
[src:google/google-p02] District Court Judge Amit Mehta ruled that Google held a monopoly in online search and text advertising in violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:google/google-p02] On October 8, 2024, The U.S. government suggested it could request Google to divest parts of its business, such as the Chrome browser and Android, due to its alleged monopoly in online search.
[src:google/google-p02] The Justice Department aimed to limit Google's growing dominance in areas like AI.
[src:google/google-p02] Google, which intended to appeal, argued that the proposals were too extreme, while also dealing with other antitrust cases involving its app store and advertising operations.
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2024, the Justice Department proposed major changes to curb Google's online search monopoly, including forcing the company to sell its Chrome browser, share search data with competitors, and end exclusive agreements that make Google the default search engine on devices like iPhones.
[src:google/google-p02] The DoJ also sought a ban on Google re-entering the browser market for five years and restrictions on its investments in rival search or AI technologies.
[src:google/google-p02] Google called these proposals excessive and harmful to consumers, pledging to appeal.
[src:google/google-p02] A trial on the case was scheduled for April 2025, though the incoming administration and new DoJ leadership could potentially alter the course of the proceedings.
[src:google/google-p02] In September 2024, Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) provisionally found that Google engaged in anti-competitive practices in the online advertising technology market, potentially harming thousands of UK publishers and advertisers.
[src:google/google-p02] The investigation claimed Google used its market power to prevent rivals from competing fairly, affecting billions spent on digital ads.
[src:google/google-p02] Google rejected the findings as flawed, stating that its ad tech benefits businesses.
[src:google/google-p02] If found guilty, Google could face penalties of up to 10% of its global turnover.
[src:google/google-p02] Similar investigations are ongoing in the U.S. and EU, where regulators have suggested that Google may need to sell part of its ad-tech business.
[src:google/google-p02] It was ruled in 2025 by the Justice Department alongside 17 other states that Google operates a monopoly in online advertising technology.
[src:google/google-p02] The case will now move to a remedies stage which may lead to Alphabet, the owner of Google, being broken up.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2017, three women sued Google, accusing the company of violating California's Equal Pay Act by underpaying its female employees.
[src:google/google-p02] The lawsuit cited the wage gap was around $17,000 and that Google locked women into lower career tracks, leading to smaller salaries and bonuses.
[src:google/google-p02] In June 2022, Google agreed to pay a $118 million settlement to 15,550 female employees working in California since 2013.
[src:google/google-p02] As a part of the settlement, Google also agreed to hire a third party to analyze its hiring and compensation practices.
[src:google/google-p02] According to Ryan Gallagher of *The Intercept* in August 2018, Google was developing for the People's Republic of China a censored version of its search engine (known as Dragonfly) "that will blacklist websites and search terms about human rights, democracy, religion, and peaceful protest".
[src:google/google-p02] Google was grilled at a Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation hearing on the project one month later.
[src:google/google-p02] The project was canceled in December following the backlash it garnered both externally and internally within the company.
[src:google/google-p02] In May 2024, a misconfiguration in Google Cloud led to the accidental deletion of UniSuper's $135 billion Australian pension fund account, affecting over half a million members who were unable to access their accounts for a week.
[src:google/google-p02] The outage, attributed to a cloud service error and not a cyberattack, prompted a joint apology from UniSuper and Google Cloud executives, who assured members that no personal data was compromised and restoration efforts were underway.
[src:google/google-p02] On October 8, 2018, a class action lawsuit was filed against Google and Alphabet due to "non-public" Google+ account data being exposed as a result of a bug that allowed app developers to gain access to the private information of users.
[src:google/google-p02] The litigation was settled in July 2020 for $7.5 million with a payout to claimants of at least $5 each, with a maximum of $12 each.
[src:google/google-p02] On January 21, 2019, French data regulator CNIL imposed a record €50 million fine on Google for breaching the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:google/google-p02] The judgment claimed Google had failed to sufficiently inform users of its methods for collecting data to personalize advertising.
[src:google/google-p02] Google issued a statement saying it was "deeply committed" to transparency and was "studying the decision" before determining its response.
[src:google/google-p02] In November 2019, the Office for Civil Rights of the Department of Health and Human Services began investigation into Project Nightingale, to assess whether the "mass collection of individuals' medical records" complied with the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act.
[src:google/google-p02] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, Google secretively began the project in 2018, with St.
[src:google/google-p02] Louis-based healthcare company Ascension.
[src:google/google-p02] In early June 2020, a $5 billion class-action lawsuit was filed against Google by a group of consumers, alleging that Chrome's Incognito browsing mode still collects their user history.
[src:google/google-p02] The lawsuit became known in March 2021 when a federal judge denied Google's request to dismiss the case, ruling that they must face the group's charges.
[src:google/google-p02] Reuters reported that the lawsuit alleged that Google's CEO Sundar Pichai sought to keep the users unaware of this issue.
[src:google/google-p02] In April 2024, it was announced that Google agreed to settle this lawsuit.
[src:google/google-p02] Under the terms of the settlement Google agreed to destroy billions of data records to settle a lawsuit claiming it secretly tracked the internet use of people who thought they were browsing privately.
[src:google/google-p02] On January 6, 2022, France's data privacy regulatory body CNIL fined Alphabet's Google 150 million euros (US$169 million) for not allowing its Internet users an easy refusal of cookies along with Facebook.
[src:google/google-p02] In August 2024, Google sent an email to users informing them of its legal obligation to disclose certain confidential information to U.S. government authorities.
[src:google/google-p02] In January 2025, U.S. federal judge Richard Seeborg rejected Google's motion to dismiss a class-action lawsuit.
[src:google/google-p02] The lawsuit claims Google collected data from users who had specifically opted out of tracking.
[src:google/google-p02] In September 2025, a federal jury decided that Google must pay $425 million.
[src:google/google-p02] Google said it would appeal the decision.
[src:google/google-p02] Google has been criticized for continuing to collect location data from users who had turned off location-sharing settings.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2020, the FBI used a geofence warrant to request data from Google about Android devices near the Seattle Police Officers Guild building following an arson attempt during Black Lives Matter protests.
[src:google/google-p02] Google provided anonymized location data from devices in the area, which raised privacy concerns due to the potential inclusion of unrelated protesters.
[src:google/google-p02] On March 20, 2024, Google was fined approximately $270 million by French regulators for using content from news outlets in France without proper disclosure to train its AI, Bard, now renamed Gemini, violating a previous commitment to negotiate content use transparently and fairly.
[src:google/google-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, the NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Google.
[src:google/google-p02] According to unnamed sources, Google joined the PRISM program in 2009, as YouTube in 2010.
[src:google/google-p02] Department of Defense (DoD) on drone software through the 2017 Project Maven that could be used to improve the accuracy of drone strikes.
[src:google/google-p02] In April 2018, thousands of Google employees, including senior engineers, signed a letter urging Google CEO Sundar Pichai to end this controversial contract with the Pentagon.
[src:google/google-p02] Google ultimately decided not to renew this DoD contract, which was set to expire in 2019.
[src:google/google-p02] In 2022 Google shared a $9 billion contract from the Pentagon for cloud computing with Amazon, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:google/google-p02] In February 2019, a privacy incident involving the Google Nest Guard system went public.
[src:google/google-p02] The controversy stemmed from the fact that Nest Guard, a security device that was part of the Nest Secure system, contained a hidden microphone that was not disclosed in any product specifications.
[src:google/google-p02] It resulted in a public relations failure.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Google's marketing website for .zip states that it is intended "for tying things together or moving really fast".
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] As with a number of other gTLDs, Google require registrants to use HTTPS.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] The qualifier `.zip` is also associated with the widely recognized .zip file format, commonly used for file compression and archiving, and its approval as a gTLD received criticism for the security concerns that may arise as a consequence.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Google opened registration for the .zip and .mov top-level domains to the general public on May 3, 2023.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Its release was immediately met with condemnation from cyber security experts as a result of its similarity with the file format of the same name.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Malwarebytes warned against the use of already recognizable filenames and their confusion with top-level domains, as "plenty of users already have a clear idea that .zip means something completely different".
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Experts cautioned against their use, and noted that the use of .zip filetypes in cybercrime had had "an explosion" in recent years.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Cisco warned against the potential for leaks for personal identifying information.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Researchers also registered similar concern about Google's .mov domain.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Following its release to the general public, .zip domain registrations were one of the most popular new domains registered in mid-2023, during the domain's landrush and early access period.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Security researchers noted high levels of phishing domains and high levels of redirection campaigns.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Shortly after its release, some security vendors blocked access to .zip domains, and new domains under these TLDs began to be scrutinized more carefully.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] One month after its public release in June 2023, there were 13,796 .zip domains registered; which rose to over 14,000 as of November 2024.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] Security researchers found that the rate of malicious registrations for the domain was approximately 0.20%, slightly below the global average of 0.22%.
[src:google/zip-top-level-domain] This was still higher than the abuse rate of 0.06% seen in European ccTLDs.
